  body "ْیا حال ہَے؟}}, {{t|ur|آپ کَیسے ہَیں؟}} {{qualifier|formal}}, {{t|ur|کَیسے ہو؟}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Uyghur: {{t-needed|ug}}\n* Uzbek: {{t|uz|qalaysan?}}, {{t|uz|qalaysiz?}}\n* Veps: {{t|vep|kut"
  body " elät?}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t|vi|khoẻ không?}}, {{t|vi|khoẻ chứ?}}, {{t|vi|dạo này sao?}}, {{t|vi|ăn cơm chưa?}}, {{t|vi|ăn cơm chửa?}} {{qualifier|Thanh Hóa}}\n* Volapük: {{t|vo|lio stadol-li?}}\n* Võr"
  body "o: {{t|vro|kuis lätt?}}\n* Votic: {{t|vot|kui meneb?}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|ké novele|alt=ké novele?}}, {{t+|wa|ké novele a Lidje|alt=ké novele a Lidje?}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{t+|wa|ça vos va|alt="
  body "ça vos va?}}, {{t+|wa|ça_t’_va}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|sut wyt ti|alt=sut wyt ti?}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{t|cy|sut dach chi|alt=sut dach chi?}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* Winnebago:"
  body " {{t|win|jaanįsge raje?}}\n* Xhosa: {{t|xh|unjani?}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|וואָס הערט זיך בײַ דיר?}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{t|yi|וואָס מאַכסטו?}} {{qualifier|familiar}}, {{t|yi|וואָס מאַכט איר?}} {{qu"
  body "alifier|formal}}, {{t|yi|וואָס מאַכט אַ ייִד?}} {{qualifier|casual, to another Jew}}, {{t|yi|וואָס טוט זיך?}} {{qualifier|casual}}, {{t|yi|וואָס הערט זיך?}}\n* Yoruba: {{t|yo|ṣé àlàáfíà l'ẹ wà}}? {{qu"
  body "alifier|polite}}, {{t|yo|ṣé àlàáfíà ni}}?, {{t|yo|ṣé dáadáa ni}}?, {{t|yo|báwo ni}}? {{qualifier|casual}}\n* Yucatec Maya: {{t|yua|¿bix a beel?}}\n* Yup'ik: {{t|esu|qaillun ayuqsit?}}, {{t|esu|cangaci"
  body "t?}}\n* Zazaki: {{t|zza|senin ê?}}, {{t|zza|hal kêf}}\n* Zulu: {{t+|zu|unjani?}} {{qualifier|singular}}, {{t|zu|ninjani?}} {{qualifier|plural}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=a"
  body "ehooruwy|who are you}}\n\n{{cln|en|questions|sentences|greetings}}""}}"

response_0022_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=how_do_you_do&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""how do you do"",""pageid"":276058,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""==English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|en|how-do-you-do}}, {{l|en|how-d'ye-do}}, {{l|en|how-de-do}} {{qualifier|noun"
  body "}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|en|En-au-how do you do.ogg|a=AU}}\n\n===Phrase===\n{{en-head|phr|head=?}}\n\n# {{lb|en|formal|dated}} {{ng|A greeting used upon being introduced to someone. Altern"
  body "atives are [[how are you]], [[pleased to meet you]], and [[nice to meet you]]. (Sometimes used as a rhetorical question among familiar parties, depending on the region).}}\n#* {{RQ:Porter Pollyanna|ch"
  body "apter=8|passage=\""'''How do you do'''?\"" began Pollyanna politely. \""I'm from Miss Polly Harrington, and I'd like to see Mrs. Snow, please.\""}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nThis phrase can be inflected: \"""
  body "I asked him how he was doing\"" or (obsolete) \""I asked him how he did\"".\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|how are you doing}} (less formal)\n* {{l|en|howdy}} (informal)\n\n====Translations====\n{{tr"
  body "ans-top|Phrase: how do you do}}\n* Abkhaz: {{qualifier|to a woman}} {{t|ab|бышҧаҟоу}}, {{qualifier|to a man}} {{t|ab|ушҧаҟоу}}, {{qualifier|to more than one person}} {{t|ab|шәышҧаҟақоу}}\n* Arabic: {{"
  body "t|ar|تَشَرَّفْنَا}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|encantáu}} {{qualifier|said by a male}}, {{t+|ast|encantada}} {{qualifier|said by a female}}, {{t|ast|Encantáu de coñocete}}, {{t|ast|¿Cómu tás?}}\n* Catalan:"
  body " {{t+|ca|encantat|m}}, {{t+|ca|encantada|f}}, {{t|ca|encantat de coneixe't}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{t|yue|幸會|tr=hang6 wui6}}\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|幸會|tr=xìnghuì}}, {{t+|cmn|請多關照|tr=qǐng duō guā"
  body "nzhào}}, {{t+|cmn|您好|tr=nínhǎo}}, {{t|cmn|初次見面}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|těší mě}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|goddag}}, {{t|da|(det) glæder mig}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|hoe gaat het}}, {{t|nl|hoe gaat het met jou}} {{q|i"
  body "nformal}}, {{t|nl|hoe gaat het met u}} {{q|formal}}, {{t|nl|hoe maakt u het}} {{q|formal, dated}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|kuidas läheb}}\n* Faroese: {{t|fo|hvussu gongur}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hyvää päivää"
  body "}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|enchanté|m}}, {{t+|fr|enchantée|f}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|encantado|m}}\n* German: {{t|de|sehr erfreut}}, {{t|de|sehr angenehm}}, {{t+|de|wie geht es dir}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|χαίρω "
  body "πολύ}}\n* Hiligaynon: {{t|hil|kamusta}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|örvendek}}, {{t+|hu|örvendek a szerencsének}}, {{t+|hu|örülök, hogy megismerhetem}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|apa kabar?}}\n* Italian: {{t|it"
  body "|piacere di conoscerla|m|f}}, {{t|it|come va}}, {{t|it|tutto bene}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|初めまして|tr=はじめまして, hajimemashite}}, {{qualifier|very formal}} {{t|ja|始めてお目にかかります|tr=はじめておめにかかります, hajimete o-me n"
  body "i kakarimasu}}, {{t+|ja|御機嫌よう}}, {{t+|ja|ご機嫌よう|tr=ごきげんよう, gokigen yō}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|сәлеметсіз бе}}, {{t|kk|амансыз ба}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|안녕-하십니까}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|[[quid]] [[agis]]?}} {{qualif"
  body "ier|said to one person}}, {{t|la|[[quid]] [[agitis]]?}} {{qualifier|said to more than one person}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|мило ми е}}, {{t|mk|драго ми е}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|nizhónígo ałhééhosiilzįįd}}\"
  body "n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: formal: {{t|no|gleder meg|lit=I am pleased (to meet you)}}, more informal: {{t|no|hyggelig å møte deg}}, {{t|no|hvordan har du det}}\n* Persian: {{t|fa|از آشنایی شما خوشوقتم|"
  body "tr=az âšenâyi-ye šomâ xošvaqtam}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|jak się masz}} {{qualifier|informal, to a singular listener}}, {{t|pl|jak się macie}} {{qualifier|informal, to many listeners}}, {{t+|pl|jak leci}}"
  body " {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|pl|jak tam}} {{qualifier|informal}}, {{t+|pl|co słychać?}}, {{t|pl|miło mi Państwa poznać}} {{q|formally}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|muito prazer}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|о́чен"
  body "ь прия́тно}}, {{t+|ru|как дела́?}}, {{t|ru|прия́тно познако́миться}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|encantado}} {{qualifier|said by a male}}, {{t+|es|encantada}} {{qualifier|said by a female}}, {{t|es|¿cómo está"
  body " usted?}}\n* Swedish: {{t|sv|hur står det till}} {{qualifier|formal}}, {{t|sv|hur är det med dig}} {{qualifier|informal}}\n* Tagalog: {{t+|tl|kumusta}}\n* Tillamook: {{t|til|dəʔ šʔálen̓əxʷš}}\n* Turki"
  body "sh: {{t|tr|nasılsınız}} (formal), {{t|tr|ne var ne yok}} (informal)\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|UK|euphemism}} A [[difficult]] [[situation]]\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1993"
  body "|author=Nick Park|title=Wallace and Gromit: The Wrong Trousers|passage=Well, this is a fine '''how do you do''' isn't it, Gromit?}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Michael Sledge|title=The More I"
  body " Owe You: A Novel|publisher=Counterpoint Press|isbn=9781582435763|page=78\n|passage=On the winding road to Petropolis, they did not speak, not about modernism or the construction of houses or antique "
  body "bird jails or fine '''how-do-you-dos'''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2013|author=Chris Raschka|title=Seriously, Norman!|publisher=Scholastic Inc.|isbn=9780545388467|page=115\n|passage=\""Vienna!\"" Mr. B"
  body ". went on. \""This is a bit of a '''how-do-you-do''', is it not?\""}}\n\n{{cln|en|phrasebook|rhetorical questions|greetings}}""}}"

response_0023_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=however&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""however"",""pageid"":4794,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""==English==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|however}}, {{m|enm|how-ever}}, {{m|enm|how-evere}}; equivalent to {{univ|en|how|e"
  body "ver|notext=1}}. Compare {{m|en|howsoever}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/haʊˈɛvə/|a=RP}}\n* {{enPR|houĕvʹər|a=GA,CA}}, {{IPA|en|/haʊˈɛvɚ/}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-however.ogg|a=California}}\n* {{"
  body "IPA|en|/hɑˈwɛvə(ɹ)/|a=NYC}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hæɔˈevə/|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/hæʊˈevə/|a=NZ}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛvə(ɹ)|s=3}}\n* {{hyphenation|en|how|ev|er}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|conjunctive"
  body "}} {{U|nevertheless}}; [[yet]], [[still]]; [[in spite of]] that.\n#: {{syn|en|nonetheless|notwithstanding|that said|still and all|in any case|after all|anyway|Thesaurus:nevertheless|Thesaurus:regardle"
  body "ss}}\n#: {{cot|en|but<qq:conjunction>}}<!--different POS but same meaning-->\n#: {{ux|en|He told me not to do it. '''However''', I did it anyway. / I did it anyway, '''however'''. / I, '''however''', "
  body "did it anyway.}}\n#: {{ux|en|She wanted to go; '''however''', she decided against it.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I didn't argue with him; I still think, '''however''', that he is wrong.}}\n#* {{RQ:Besant Ivory Gat"
  body "e|chapter=Prologue|passage=Thus, when he drew up instructions in lawyer language, he expressed the important words by an initial, a medial, or a final consonant, and made scratches for all the words b"
  body "etween; his clerks, '''however''', understood him very well.}}\n#* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=2|passage=''That'' the young Mr. Churchills liked—but they did not like him coming round of "
  body "an evening and drinking weak whisky-and-water while he held forth on railway debentures and corporation loans. Mr. Barrett, '''however''', by fawning and flattery, seemed to be able to make not only M"
  body "rs. Churchill but everyone else do what he desired.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-29|volume=407|issue=8842|page=72–3|magazine=w:The Economist\n|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/internation"
  body "al/science-and-technology/21580133-how-microbes-promote-liver-cancer-overweight-punch-gut A punch in the gut]\n|passage=Mostly, the microbiome is beneficial. It helps with digestion and enables people"
  body " to extract a lot more calories from their food than would otherwise be possible. Research over the past few years, '''however''', has implicated it in diseases from atherosclerosis to asthma to autis"
  body "m.}}\n# {{lb|en|conjunctive}} In [[contrast]].\n#: {{ux|en|The conference itself went very well. The party afterwards, '''however''', was a disaster.}}\n# {{lb|en|degree|fused relative}} {{U|regardles"
  body "s of}} [[how]]; [[no matter]] [[how]]\n#: {{syn|en|howsoever|howso|howsoevermuch}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''However''' clear you think you've been, and '''however''' many questions you [[may've]] answered, ther"
  body "e'll always remain some doubts.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Any rule of thumb, '''however''' true (it is), is useless unless you understand its underlying logic.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''However''' much I study, I never ge"
  body "t good grades.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1811|author=[[s:Author:Jane Austen|Jane Austen]]|title=s:Sense and Sensibility|section=[[s:Sense and Sensibility/Chapter 42|Chapter 42]]|passage=Elinor, '''ho"
  body "wever''' little concerned in it, joined in their discourse; and Marianne, who had the knack of finding her way in every house to the library, however it might be avoided by the family in general, soon"
  body " procured herself a book.}}\n# {{lb|en|manner|fused relative}} {{U|regardless of}} [[how]]; [[regardless of]] the way in which.\n#: {{syn|en|howsoever|howso|anyhow}}\n#: {{ux|en|Let me know when you'v"
  body "e had your interview, '''however''' it goes.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''However''' we do this, it isn't going to work.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1811|author=[[s:Author:Jane Austen|Jane Austen]]|title=s:Sense a"
  body "nd Sensibility|section=[[s:Sense and Sensibility/Chapter 42|Chapter 42]]|passage=Elinor, however little concerned in it, joined in their discourse; and Marianne, who had the knack of finding her way i"
  body "n every house to the library, '''however''' it might be avoided by the family in general, soon procured herself a book.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-21|author=w:Oliver Burkeman\n|volume=189|i"
  body "ssue=2|page=48|magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly\n|title=[http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/may/10/conscious-computing-twitter-facebook-google The tao of tech]\n|passage=But the real way to buil"
  body "d a successful online business is to be better than your rivals at undermining people's control of their own attention. Partly, this is a result of how online advertising has traditionally worked: adv"
  body "ertisers pay for clicks, and a click is a click, '''however''' it's obtained.}}\n# {{lb|en|manner|fused relative}} In any [[way]] in which; [[how]].\n#: {{ux|en|She offered to help '''however''' she c"
  body "ould.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Wear your hair '''however''' you want.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal|manner}} In any way that one likes or chooses; in a haphazard or spontaneous way.\n#: {{ux|en|I don't care; just do it "
  body "'''however'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Nothing was really planned; things just happened '''however'''.}}\n# {{senseid|en|interrogative}} {{lb|en|interrogative}} [[how|How]] [[ever]]: {{non-gloss|an emphatic for"
  body "m of '''''[[how]]''''', used to ask in what manner}}.\n#: {{syn|en|[[how]] + [[the dickens]]|Thesaurus:the dickens}}\n#: {{cot|en|whatever<id:interrogative>}}\n#: {{ux|en|I thought it was impossible. "
  body "'''However''' were you able to do it?}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[in any case|In any case]], [[at any rate]], [[at all events]].\n#* {{circa|1680}}, John Tillotson:\n#*: Our chief end and highest intere"
  body "st is happiness : And this is happiness to be freed from all (if it may) [or] '''however''' from the greatest evils.\n\n====Usage notes====\nTraditionally, some commentators have objected to the use o"
  body "f \""however\"" at the start of a sentence in the sense of \""nevertheless\"", but in practice this is widely accepted if followed immediately by a comma. The choice of position depends on the word being "
  body "emphasized, which is usually the one immediately before.\n\nThe use of a comma before \""however\"" as a means of connecting independent clauses in the sense of \""nevertheless\"", as in \""She wanted to g"
  body "o, '''however''' she decided against it\"", is traditionally considered an error, equivalent to using \""however\"" as a proscribed conjunction (see below). Compare the prescriptively correct sentence \"""
  body "She wanted to go, <u>but</u> she decided against it\"", which uses a true conjunction \""but\"". Similarly, mispunctuating it between commas makes for an ambiguous modifier because '''however''' could go"
  body " with either clause.\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|en|however one slices it}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top-see|nevertheless|nevertheless|that being said}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|megjithatë}}\n"
  body "* Arabic: {{t+|ar|لٰكِن}}, {{t+|ar|لٰكِنَّ}}, {{t|ar|وَلٰكِن|tr=wa-lākin}}, {{t|ar|وَلٰكِنَّ|tr=wa-lākinna}}, {{t|ar|رَغْمَ ذٰلِك}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|وخى هد شي|tr=waḵa had ši}}\n* Armenian:"
  body " {{t+|hy|սակայն}}\n* Asturian: {{t|ast|sin embargu}}\n* Basque: {{t+|eu|haatik}}\n* Belarusian: {{t+|be|адна́к}}, {{t|be|тым не ме́нш}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|оба́че}}\n* Burmese: {{t+|my|ဒါပေမဲ့}}\n* "
  body "Catalan: {{t+|ca|tanmateix}}, {{t+|ca|nogensmenys}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|但是|tr=dànshì}}, {{t+|cmn|可是|tr=kěshì}}, {{t+|cmn|不過|tr=búguò}}, {{t+|cmn|卻|tr=què}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|nicméně}}, "
  body "{{t+|cs|však}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|dog}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|daarentegen}}, {{t+|nl|echter}}, {{t+|nl|evenwel}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|kontraŭe}}, {{t+|eo|tamen}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kuitenkin}}\n* French:"
  body " {{t+|fr|cependant}}, {{t+|fr|pourtant}}, {{t+|fr|néanmoins}}, {{t+|fr|toutefois}}, {{t+|fr|nonobstant}}\n*: Old French: {{t|fro|nepourquant}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|მიუხედავად ამისა}}\n* German: {{t+|de"
  body "|jedoch}}, {{t+|de|allerdings}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|όμως}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|μέντοι}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|אף על פי כן}}, {{t|he|למרות זאת}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|फिर भी}}, {{t+|hi|यद्यपि}}\n* Hungaria"
  body "n: {{t+|hu|mégis}}, {{t+|hu|viszont}}, {{t+|hu|azonban}}, {{t+|hu|mindazonáltal}}\n* Ilocano: {{t|ilo|ngem}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|áfach}}\n*: Old Irish: {{t|sga|immurgu}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|però}}, {{t+|"
  body "it|nonostante}}, {{t+|it|tuttavia}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|しかし|tr=shikashi}}, {{t+|ja|が|tr=ga}}, {{t+|ja|でも|tr=demo}}, {{t+|ja|けれども|tr=keredomo}}, {{t+|ja|けれど|tr=keredo}}, {{t|ja|けども|tr=kedomo}}, {{t+|j"
  body "a|けど|tr=kedo}}\n* Kapampangan: {{t|pam|onyang}} {{qualifier|formally}}, {{t|pam|oneng}} {{qualifier|colloquially}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|그러나}}, {{t+|ko|하지만}}, {{t+|ko|나|alt=-(으)나}}, {{t+|ko|지만|alt=-지만}},"
  body " {{t+|ko|만|alt=-만}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t+|kmr|her wiha}}, {{t+|kmr|dîsa jî}}, {{t+|kmr|lê}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|tamen}}, {{t|la|utut}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|ndé}}\n* Lushootseed: {{t|lut|ʔ"
  body "iwəɬ}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{t+|lb|awer}}, {{t+|lb|awer}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|меѓутоа}}\n* Malay: {{t|ms|walau bagaimana}}\n* Maltese: {{t|mt|madankollu}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|ikke desto "
  body "mindre}}, {{t+|nb|imidlertid}}, {{t+|nb|men}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|pasmens}}\n* Pannonian Rusyn: {{t|rsk|заш лєм}}, {{t|rsk|медзитим}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|اما|tr=ammâ}}, {{t|fa|با این حال}}\n* Polish: "
  body "{{t+|pl|jednakże}}, {{t+|pl|jednak}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|no entanto}}, {{t+|pt|entretanto}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|totuși}}, {{t+|ro|însă}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|одна́ко}}, {{t+|ru|тем не ме́нее}}\n* S"
  body "cots: {{t|sco|houaniver}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|ge-tà}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|међутим}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|međutim}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|však}}\n* Slovene: {{t|sl|vendar}}\n* Sorb"
  body "ian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|pak}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|sin embargo}}, {{t+|es|no obstante}}, {{t+|es|mas}}, {{t+|es|empero}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|däremot}}, {{t+|sv|dock}}, {{t+|sv|emellertid}}\n* T"
  body "agalog: {{t|tl|subalit}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|อย่างไรก็ตาม|tr=yàang rai gôr dtaam}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|bununla birlikte}}, {{t+|tr|ancak}}, {{t+|tr|lakin}}, {{t+|tr|fakat}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|одна́к}},"
  body " {{t|uk|проте́}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|biroq}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|tuy nhiên}}\n* Votic: {{t|vot|sorovnoo}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|portant}}, {{t+|wa|mins nerén}}, {{t|wa|mågré tot}}\n* West Flemish: {{t|"
  body "vls|pertank}}\n* Zazaki: {{t+|zza|labelê}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to whatever extent or degree}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|все пак}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|kiom ajn}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[kuinka]] "
  body "[[tahansa]]}}, {{t|fi|[[miten]] [[tahansa]]}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|peu importe}}\n* German: {{t|de|[[egal]] [[wie]]}}\n* Hungarian: {{gloss|with verbs or predicate adjectives}} {{t+|hu|bármennyire}} / {"
  body "{t+|hu|akármennyire}}, {{gloss|with predicate adjectives only}} {{t+|hu|bármilyen}} / {{t+|hu|akármilyen}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|dá}} {{qualifier|followed by abstract noun}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|сепак}}\n"
  body "* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|uansett hvor}}, {{t|nb|uten omsyn til hvor}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|comoquiera}}, {{t|es|comoquier}}, {{t+|es|como sea}}, {{t|es|[[cuantoquiera]] [[que]]}} {{q|however much"
  body "|rare}}, {{t|es|[[cuanto]] [[sea]]}} {{q|however much}}, {{t|es|así como así}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|er mor}}, {{t|cy|pa mor}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|no matter how}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|por más q"
  body "ue}}, {{t|es|[[aunque]] más}}, {{t|es|[[por]] [[muy]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|in any way in which}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|[[comoquiera]] que}}, {{t|es|[[como sea]] [[que]]}} {{q|present}}, {{t"
  body "|es|[[como]] [[fuere]] [[que]]}} {{q|future}}, {{t|es|[[como]] [[fuese]] [[que]]}} {{q|past}}, {{t|es|[[como]] [[fuera]] [[que]]}} {{q|past}}, {{t|es|[[de cualquier manera]] [[que]]}}, {{t|es|[[de cua"
  body "lquier modo]] [[que]]}}, {{t|es|[[de cualquier manera]] [[que]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top-see|in any way that one likes or chooses|anyway}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|mal que bien}}, {{t|es|bien que"
  body " mal}}, {{t|es|comoquiera}}, {{t|es|comoquier}}, {{t|es|de cualquier modo}}, {{t|es|de cualquier forma}}, {{t|es|de cualquier manera}}, {{t+|es|como sea}} {{q|present}}, {{t|es|[[como]] [[fuese]]}} {{"
  body "q|past}}, {{t|es|[[como]] [[fuera]]}} {{q|past}}, {{t|es|[[como]] [[fuere]]}} {{q|future}}, {{t|es|[[así]] que asá}}, {{t|es|[[así]] que asado}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Czech: {{t+|"
  body "cs|jakkoli}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|eender hoe}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[miten]] [[tahansa]]}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|akármennyire}} ({{t+|hu|is}}), {{t+|hu|bármennyire}} ({{t+|hu|is}})\n* Indonesian: {{t+check"
  body "|id|tapi}}, {{t+check|id|tetapi}}, {{t+check|id|namun}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|arae}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|på den måten}}, {{t|no|på hvilken måte}}; {{t|no|uansett hvor}}, {{t|no|hvor mye}}\n* Romanian: {{t"
  body "+|ro|oricum}}; {{t|ro|oricât de}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|hur som helst}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|ye}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}} <!-- correspond either to \""no matter how\"" or \""in any way in wh"
  body "ich\"", which was originally listed as one sense, \""in whatever way or manner\"" -->\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|كَيْفَ}}, {{t|ar|كَيْفَمَا}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|hoe dan ook}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|kiel ajn}}\n* Fren"
  body "ch: {{t|fr|de quelque manière que ce soit}}, {{t|fr|quelle que soit sa manière}}\n* German: {{t|de|wie auch immer}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|akárhogy}} ({{t+|hu|is}}), {{t+|hu|akárhogyan}} ({{t+|hu|is}})"
  body ", {{t+|hu|bárhogy}} ({{t+|hu|is}}), {{t+|hu|bárhogyan}} ({{t+|hu|is}}), {{t|hu|ahogy csak}}, {{t|hu|ahogyan csak}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|comunque}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|de qualquer modo}}\n{{trans-bott"
  body "om}}\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{en-head|conj}}\n\n# {{lb|en|proscribed}} {{U|but}}, [[yet]], [[though]], [[although]].\n#: {{ux|en|*She wanted to go, '''however''' she decided against it.|q=proscribed}}\"
  body "n\n====Usage notes====\nSee the usage notes for adverb senses, above.\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Webster 1913|however}}\n* {{R:Dictionary.com|however}}\n* \""[https://web.archive.org/web/20071208172827"
  body "/http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=38295&dict=CALD however (degree)]\"" in Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary (Cambridge University Press, 2007)\n* \""[https://web.archive.org/web/2007"
  body "1208172837/http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=38298&dict=CALD however (despite)]\"" in Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary (Cambridge University Press, 2007)\n* \""[https://web.archive.o"
  body "rg/web/20071208172832/http://dictionary.cambridge.org/define.asp?key=38296&dict=CALD however (way)]\"" in Cambridge Advanced Learner's Dictionary (Cambridge University Press, 2007)\n* {{R:Lexico|howeve"
  body "r}}\n* ''Oxford English Dictionary'', second edition (1989)\n* ''Random House Webster's Unabridged Electronic Dictionary'' (1987-1996)\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=eehorvw|everwho|whoever}}\n\"
  body "n{{cln|en|conjunctive adverbs|degree adverbs|intensifiers}}""}}"

response_0024_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=is_it&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""is it"",""pageid"":3785703,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""{{also|isit}}\n==English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|issit||Singapore}}\n* {{alt|en|izit||South Africa}}\n* {{alt|en|"
  body "izzit}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/(ˈ)ɪz ɪt/}}\n* {{audio|en|En-us-is it.ogg|a=US}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{en-intj}}\n\n# {{&lit|en|is|it}}\n#: {{ux|en|- It's ten o'clock already.<br>- '''I"
  body "s it'''?}}\n# {{lb|en|Canada|South Africa|Indian English|MLE|MTE}} [[really]]? [[is that so]]?\n#: {{ux|en|- I'm feeling tired.<br>- '''Is it'''?}}\n#* '''2007''', Dan le Sac vs. Scroobius Pip, \""Thou"
  body " Shalt Always Kill\"" on ''Angles''\n#*: Thou shalt not express your shock at the fact that Sharon got off with Brad at the club last night by saying \""'''is it'''?\""\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=2011-07-3"
  body "1|author=James Ashcroft|title=Making A Killing: The Explosive Story of a Hired Gun in Iraq|publisher=Random House|isbn=9780753547748|page=80\n|text='Everyone just calls me Ash.'<br/>{{'}}'''Izzit'''?'"
  body " said Hendriks, and he fixed me with his cold grey eyes. Spartan at that time was unusual in that it would only take on ex-army South Africans.}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top}}\n* Spanish: {{t"
  body "|es|[[será]]}}, {{t|es|[[será]] [[cierto]]}}, {{t|es|[[será]] [[verídico]] [[eso]]}}, {{t|es|[[será]] [[verífico]] [[aqueso]]}}, {{t+|es|qué va}}, {{t+|es|quia}}, {{t+|es|ca}}, {{t+|es|jum}} {{qualifi"
  body "er|Latin America}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Particle===\n{{en-head|pcl}}\n\n# {{lb|en|Singapore|Malaysia|Wales}} {{non-gloss|Final interrogative particle forming a [[tag question]].}}\n#: {{usex|en|You"
  body " forgot, '''is it'''?}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1994|author=Michael Chiang|title=Private Parts & Other Play Things|page=242\n|passage=You think you slang-slang a bit I scared, '''is it'''? Bloody foo"
  body "l!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=Nicholas Drayson|title=A Guide to the Birds of East Africa|page=187|passage=\""I mean what now - the bet is cancelled but they are both going to ask her, '''is"
  body " it'''?\""}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2012|author=w:Tan Twan Eng|title=w:The Garden of Evening Mists|isbn=1905802498|chapter=1|page=15|publisher=Hachette|passage=So short-''{{l|en|lah|id=authoritativen"
  body "ess}}'', the chopstick. For children '''is it'''?}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nIn contrast to the neutral {{m|en|or not}}, questions formed with ''is it'' expect an affirmative response.\n\n====Synonyms="
  body "===\n*{{l|en|or not}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=iist|-itis|IIST|IITs|SITI|itis}}\n\n[[Category:Singlish]]\n[[Category:Manglish]]""}}"

response_0025_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=let&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""let"",""pageid"":7017,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""{{also|Appendix:Variations of \""let\""}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{abbrev|mul|-}} {{der|mul|en|'''Le'''sing-A'''t'''ui}}.\"
  body "n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|3}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|en|lett||archaic}}\n* {{alt|en|lettest||2nd person singul"
  body "ar simple present and simple past; archaic}}\n* {{alt|en|letteth||3rd person singular simple present; archaic}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/lɛt/}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-let.wav"
  body "|a=Southern England}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-let.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɛt|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|Lett}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{der+|en|enm|leten}}, {{m|enm|læten}}, from {{der|en|ang|lǣtan||to all"
  body "ow, let go, bequeath, leave, rent}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*lātan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*lētaną||to leave behind, allow}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*leh₁d-||to be tired, leave}}.\n\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\"
  body "nCognate with {{cog|sco|lat}}, {{m|sco|lete||to let, leave}}, {{cog|yol|leth||let}}, {{cog|frr|leet}}, {{m|frr|let}}, {{m|frr|lätje||to let}}, {{cog|bar|låssn||to let}}, {{cog|nl|-}}, {{cog|nds|laten|"
  body "|to let, leave}}, {{cog|de|lassen}}, {{m|de|laßen||to let, leave, allow}}, {{cog|lb|loossen||to let, leave}}, {{cog|yi|לאָזן||to let}}, {{cog|da|lade||to let, allow, leave}}, {{cog|fo|-}}, {{cog|is|lá"
  body "ta||to let}}, {{cog|nb|la||to let, leave}}, {{cog|nn|la}}, {{m|nn|lata}}, {{m|nn|late||let, allow}}, {{cog|sv|låta||to let, allow, leave}}, {{cog|got|𐌻𐌴𐍄𐌰𐌽||to let}}, {{cog|sq|lë||to allow, let, leave"
  body "}} and partially related to [[French]] {{m|fr|laisser||to let}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|~s|~ting|~,leet<l:obsolete>|+,~ten<l:obsolete>}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[allow]] to, "
  body "not to prevent {{qualifier|+ infinitive, but usually without {{m|en|to}}}}.\n#: {{ux|en|After he knocked for hours, I decided to '''let''' him come in.}}\n#* {{RQ:KJV|Exodus|8|28|passage=Pharaoh said,"
  body " I will '''let''' you go.}}\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|act=IV|scene=vi|passage=If your name be Horatio, as I am '''let''' to know it is{{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1971|author=w:Ursula K. Le Gu"
  body "in|title=w:The Tombs of Atuan\n|passage=He could not be '''let'''<!--sic--> die of thirst there alone in the dark.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-21|author=w:Oliver Burkeman| volume=189| issue="
  body "2| page=27| magazine=w:The Guardian Weekly| title=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2013/may/10/conscious-computing-twitter-facebook-google The tao of tech]| passage=The dirty secret of the intern"
  body "et is that all this distraction and interruption is immensely profitable. Web companies like to boast about [&hellip;], or offering services that '''let''' you \""stay up to date with what your friends"
  body " are doing\"",{{...}}and so on. But the real way to build a successful online business is to be better than your rivals at undermining people's control of their own attention.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}}"
  body " To allow to be or do without interference; to not disturb or meddle with; to [[leave alone]].\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' me be!}}\n#* {{RQ:Spenser Faerie Queene|book=II|canto=VI|stanza=16|passage=Yet neit"
  body "her spinnes nor cardes, ne cares nor frets, / But to her mother Nature all her care she '''lets'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To allow the release of (a fluid).\n#: {{ux|en|The physicians '''let''' ab"
  body "out a pint of his blood, but to no avail.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|chiefly|British}} To allow possession of (a property etc.) in exchange for [[rent]].\n#: {{ux|en|I decided to '''let''' the farmhouse "
  body "to a couple while I was working abroad.}}\n#* {{RQ:Austen Pride and Prejudice|volume=I|chapter=I|pages=1–2|passage=“My dear Mr. Bennet,” said his lady to him one day, “have you heard that Netherfield "
  body "Park is '''let''' at last?”<br>Mr. Bennet replied that he had not.<br>“But it is,” returned she; “for Mrs. Long has just been here, and she told me all about it.”}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|text=Trailers f"
  body "or sale or rent, rooms to '''let''', fifty cents.|year=1965|author=Roger Miller|title=King Of The Road}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give, grant, or assign, as a work, privilege, or contract; often wit"
  body "h ''out''.\n#: {{ux|en|to '''let''' the building of a bridge; &emsp;to '''let''' out the lathing and the plastering}}\n# {{lb|en|auxiliary|transitive}} {{non-gloss|Used to introduce a first or third p"
  body "erson imperative verb construction.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''''s put on a show!}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' us have a moment of silence.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''Let''' me just give you the phone number.}}\n#: {{ux|"
  body "en|'''Let''' ''P'' be the point where ''AB'' and ''OX'' intersect.}}\n#: {{ux|en|\""'''Let''' there be no doubt: I saw you boyfriend with another girl\"" \""'''Let''' him. I don't care anymore\"".}}\n# {{"
  body "lb|en|transitive|obsolete|_|except with [[know]] or [[be]]}} To [[cause]] {{qualifier|+ bare infinitive}}.\n#: {{ux|en|Can you '''let''' me know what time you'll be arriving?}}\n#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtDrthr|"
  body "6.4|2|IV|iv|passage=Soo within a whyle kynge Pellinore cam with a grete hoost and salewed the peple and the kyng and ther was grete ioye made on euery syde. Thenne the kyng '''lete''' serche how moche"
  body " people of his party ther was slayne. And ther were founde but lytel past two honderd men slayne and viij knyȝtes of the table round in their pauelions.|t=So after a while King Pellinore came with a g"
  body "reat host and saluted the people and the king, and there was great joy on every side. Then the king '''let''' search how many people of his faction were slain. And there were found only a little more "
  body "than two hundred men slain, and eight knights of the Table Round in their pavilions.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1818|author=w:John Keats|title=To—\n|passage=Time's sea hath been five years at its slow"
  body " ebb, / Long hours have to and fro '''let''' creep the sand{{nb...}}.}}\n#* {{RQ:Thoreau Walden|chapter=The Ponds|page=212|passage=What right had the unclean and stupid farmer, whose farm abutted on t"
  body "his sky water, whose shores he has ruthlessly laid bare, to give his name to it? ... Rather '''let''' it be named from the fishes that swim in it, the wild fowl or quadrupeds which frequent it, the wi"
  body "ld flowers which grow by its shores, or some wild man or child the thread of whose history is interwoven with its own...}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* The use of “let” to introduce an imperative may s"
  body "ometimes be confused with its use, ''as its own imperative'', in the sense of “to allow”. For example, the sentence “'''Let''' me go to the store.” could either be a second-person imperative of “let” "
  body "(addressing someone who might prevent the speaker from going to the store) or a first-person singular imperative of “go” (not implying any such preventer).\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|to allow}} "
  body "{{l|en|allow}}, {{l|en|permit}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|bloodlet|lettable|letter|lettor|relet|unlet\n|buy-to-let,buy to let\n|don't let the bedbugs bite\n|don't let the door hit you on t"
  body "he way out\n|forlet\n|if it's yellow let it mellow|let a sleeping dog lie|let things alone|let things be\n|inlet\n|let alone\n|let a thousand flowers bloom\n|let be\n|let blood\n|let bygones be bygone"
  body "s\n|let down\n|let drive\n|let fluffy off the chain|let crazy stick its dick in you|let into|let one's nuts hang|let this cup pass from me|let through|ship and let ship\n|let fly\n|let George do it|le"
  body "t someone hold\n|let go|let me tell you|let us see\n|let her rip|let that sink in\n|let he who is without sin cast the first stone\n|let him that is without sin cast the first stone\n|let him who is w"
  body "ithout sin cast the first stone\n|let in|let them eat cake\n|let in on\n|let it all hang out\n|let it alone\n|let it be\n|let it be known\n|let it snow\n|let know\n|let lie\n|let loose\n|let me count "
  body "the ways\n|let me see\n|let nature take her course\n|let Nature take its course\n|let nature take its course\n|let-off\n|let off\n|let off steam\n|let on\n|let one go\n|let one loose\n|let one off\n|l"
  body "et one rip\n|let one's guard down\n|let one's hair down\n|let one's short back and sides down\n|let out\n|let past\n|let rip\n|let's\n|let sleeping dogs lie\n|let slide\n|let slip\n|let someone have i"
  body "t\n|let someone loose\n|let something ride\n|let something slip\n|let the buyer beware\n|let the cat out\n|let the cat out of the bag\n|let the chips fall where they may\n|let the cobbler stick to his"
  body " last\n|let the devil out\n|let the dice fall where they may\n|let the dog see the rabbit\n|let the door hit you where the good Lord split you\n|let the good times roll\n|let the grass grow round one'"
  body "s feet\n|let the grass grow under one's feet\n|let the matter drop\n|let them have it\n|let the perfect be the enemy of the good\n|let there be light\n|let the sleeping dogs lie\n|let up\n|let us\n|le"
  body "t us count the ways\n|let us go\n|let well alone\n|let well enough alone\n|live-and-let-live\n|live and let live\n|offlet\n|outlet\n|re-let\n|sublet\n|take the cash and let the credit go\n|to let\n|un"
  body "derlet\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|allow}}\n* Albanian: {{t|sq|lë}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|سَمَحَ}}, {{t|ar|دَعَّ}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|خلَى|tr=ḵella}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|թողնել}"
  body "}\n* Aromanian: {{t|rup|alas}}, {{t|rup|las}}\n* Asturian: {{t+|ast|dexar}}\n* Bangi: {{t|bni|tika}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|пуска́ць|impf}}, {{t|be|пусці́ць|pf}} {{q|let go}}, {{t|be|дазваля́ць|impf}},"
  body " {{t|be|дазво́ліць|pf}}\n* Breton: {{t+|br|lezel}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|позволявам}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|permetre}}, {{t+|ca|deixar}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|讓|tr=ràng}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|"
  body "nechat}}, {{t+|cs|dovolit|pf}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|tillade}}, {{t+|da|lade}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|laten}}, {{t+|nl|toestaan}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+|eo|lasi}}, {{t|eo|permesi}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|laskma}}\n*"
  body " Finnish: {{t+|fi|antaa}}, {{t+|fi|sallia}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|laisser}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|lassâ}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|deixar}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ნების დართვა}}, {{t|ka|გაშვება}}\n* German: {{t+"
  body "|de|lassen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|επιτρέπω}}, {{t+|el|αφήνω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἐάω}}, {{t|grc|ἀφίημι}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Mbya Guarani: {{t|gun|eja}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|הִנִּיחַ|tr=hinníaẖ}}\n* Hm"
  body "ong:\n*: White Hmong: {{t-needed|mww}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|hagy}}, {{t+|hu|enged}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|leyfa}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|lasar}}\n* Interlingua: {{t|ia|lassar}}\n* Istriot: {{t|ist|lassà}}\n"
  body "* Italian: {{t+|it|lasciare}}, {{t+|it|permettere}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|させる|tr=...saseru|alt=...させる}} {{qualifier|causative form}}\n* Khmer: {{t|km|អោយ}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|허락하다}}\n* Ladin: {{t|lld|l"
  body "ascer}}\n* Lao: {{t-needed|lo}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|sinō}}, {{t+|la|patior}}, {{t|la|permittō}}, {{t+|la|sustineō}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|ļaut}}, {{t|lv|laist}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|tika}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t"
  body "+|lt|leisti}}\n* Livonian: {{t|liv|laskõ}}\n* Lombard: {{t+|lmo|lassà}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|дозволи}}\n* Neapolitan: {{t|nap|lassà}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|la}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|permetre}}, {{t+|o"
  body "c|daissar}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|lǣtan}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|گذاشتن|tr=gozâštan}}, {{t+|fa|اجازه دادن|tr=ejâze dâdan}}\n* Piedmontese: {{t|pms|lassé}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|pozwalać|impf}}, {{t+|pl|po"
  body "zwolić|pf}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|deixar}}, {{t+|pt|permitir}}, {{t+|pt|ir}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|sagii}}, {{t|qu|hagii}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|lăsa}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|laschar}}, {{t|rm|lascher}}, {{t"
  body "|rm|schar}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пуска́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|пусти́ть|pf}} {{q|let go}}, {{t+|ru|позволя́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|позво́лить|pf}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|lassai}}, {{t|sc|lassare}}\n* Scottish Gael"
  body "ic: {{t|gd|leig le}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|dopustiti}}, {{t+|sh|dati}}\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|пустити|pf}}, {{t|sh|дозволити|pf}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|pustiti|pf}}, {{t+|sh|dozvoliti|pf}}\n* Sicilian"
  body ": {{t+|scn|lassari}}\n* Slovak: {{t|sk|nechať}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|pustiti|pf}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|daś}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|permitir}}, {{t+|es|dejar}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|låta}}"
  body "\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|hayaan}}, {{t|tl|pabayaan}}\n* Telugu: {{t|te|ఇవ్వు}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ให้}}, {{t+|th|ปล่อย}}\n* Tibetan: {{t-needed|bo}}\n* Tocharian B: {{t|txb|kälm-}}, {{t|txb|tärk-}}\n* Turkis"
  body "h:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|براقمق|tr=bırakmak}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|пуска́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|пусти́ти|pf}} {{q|let go}}, {{t|uk|дозволя́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|дозво́лити|pf}}\n* Venetan: {{t+|vec|lasa"
  body "r}}\n* Vietnamese: {{t+|vi|trở|lit=to give}}, {{t+|vi|để}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|leyî}}, {{t+|wa|laire}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|gadael}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|לאָזן}}\n* Zhuang: {{t-needed|za}}\n{{trans-bottom}"
  body "}\n\n{{trans-top|leave}}\n* German: {{t+|de|lassen}}, {{t+|de|zurücklassen}}, {{t+|de|verlassen}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|براقمق|tr=bırakmak}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|allow t"
  body "he release of (a fluid)}}\n* German: {{t+|de|ablassen}}, {{t|de|herauslaufen lassen}}\n* Hebrew: {{t|he|הִקִּיז|tr=hiqqíz}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|put up for rent}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|дава"
  body "м под наем}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|出租|tr=chūzū}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|pronajmout|pf}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|verhuren}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[antaa]] [[vuokra]]lle}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|louer}}\n* "
  body "German: {{t+|de|vermieten}}, {{t+|de|überlassen}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|bérel}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|affittare}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|貸す|tr=かす, kasu}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|임대하다}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|izīrē"
  body "t}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|nuomoti}}, {{t|lt|išnuomoti}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|leie ut}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|wynajmować}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|alugar}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|[[сдава́ть]] в [[аренда|аре́нд"
  body "у]]|impf}}, {{t|ru|[[сдать]] в [[аренда|аре́нду]]|pf}}, {{t|ru|[[сдава́ть]] [[внаём]]|impf}}, {{t|ru|[[сдать]] [[внаём]]|pf}}, {{t+|ru|сдава́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|сдать|pf}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|th"
  body "oir seachad air mhàl}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|posuditi}}, {{t+|sh|iznajmiti}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|alquilar}}, {{t+|es|arrendar}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|louwer}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{tran"
  body "s-top|introducing an imperative}}\n* Belarusian: {{t|be|хай}}, {{t|be|няхай}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|нека}}, {{t+|bg|да}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|ať}}, {{t+|cs|nechť}}\n* Danish: {{t+|da|lade}}\n* Hebrew: {{"
  body "t+|he|הָבָה|tr=háva}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|niech}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|să|alt=(hai) să}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|пусть}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|хай}}, {{t|uk|нехай}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-n"
  body "oun}}\n\n# The allowing of possession of a property etc. in exchange for [[rent]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=Charles Dickens|year=1854|text=Then he says “You would call it a Good '''Let''', Madam?”<b"
  body "r>“O certainly a Good Let sir.”|page=317|title=Christmas Stories|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=g5IPAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA317&lpg=PA317&dq=You+would+call+it+a+Good+Let,+Madam?%E2%80%9D&source=bl&ots=9B"
  body "Rzev-gor&sig=ACfU3U0YQUKYQyiIkPQgMUw4tCOygSrkUQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjNtralhq3pAhUKknIEHUC3CjsQ6AEwAHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=You%20would%20call%20it%20a%20Good%20Let%2C%20Madam%3F%E2%80%9D&f=false}}\n\n"
  body "=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|holiday let}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{der+|en|enm|letten||to hinder, delay}}, from {{der|en|ang|lettan||to hinder, delay”; literally, “to make late}}, from {{der|en|g"
  body "mw-pro|*lattjan}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*latjaną}}. Akin to {{cog|ang|latian||to delay}}, {{cog|nl|letten}}, {{cog|ang|læt||late}}. More at [[late]], [[delay]].\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|+|+|+|~}}\n"
  body "\n# {{lb|en|archaic}} To [[hinder]], [[prevent]], [[impede]], [[hamper]], [[cumber]]; to [[obstruct]] {{gl|someone or something}}.\n#* {{RQ:King James Version|2 Thessalonians|2|7|passage=He who now ''"
  body "'letteth''' will '''let''', until he be taken out of the way.}}\n#* {{RQ:Tennyson Idylls|page=152|passage=Sir King, mine ancient wound is hardly whole, / And '''lets''' me from the saddle; {{...}}}}\n"
  body "# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[prevent]] someone from doing something; also to [[prevent]] something from happening.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1485|author=w:Thomas Malory|title={{w|Le Morte Darthur}} Book X"
  body "XI, Chapter ii, [https://quod.lib.umich.edu/c/cme/MaloryWks2/1:23.2?rgn=div2;view=fulltext leaf 421r]|text=''& there was syr Mordred redy awaytynge vpon his londage to '''lette''' his owne fader to lā"
  body "de vp the lande that he was kyng ouer.''<br>\""And there was Sir Mordred ready awaiting upon his landing, to '''let''' his own father to land upon the land that he was king over.\""}}\n#* {{RQ:Tyndale N"
  body "T|Acts|8|passage=And as they went on their waye, they cam unto a certayne water, and the gelded man sayde: Se here is water, what shall '''lett''' me to be baptised?}}\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[tarry"
  body "]] or [[delay]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1826|section=The History of Sir Eger, Sir Grahame, And Sir Gray-Steel|title=Early Metrical Tales; Including the History of Sir Egeir, Sir Gryme, and Sir Gray-"
  body "Steill|location=Edinburgh|page=7|passage=And for that strake I would not '''let''', / Another upon him soon I set, {{...}}}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|obsolete|or|legal}} An [[obstacle"
  body "]] or [[hindrance]].\n#: {{ux|en|without '''let''' or hindrance}}\n#* {{RQ:Latimer Sermons|volume=II|sermon=XXV|chapter=Preached on the Twenty First Sunday after Trinity|date=12 June 1552|page=541|pas"
  body "sage=[E]ver conſider vvhether our doings be to the '''let''' of our ſalvation or not.}}\n#* {{RQ:Ovid Golding Metamorphosis|book=3|lines=60–61|passage=And Cadmus saw his campanie make tarience in that"
  body " sort / He marveld what should be their '''let''', and went to seeke them out.}}\n#* {{RQ:Montaigne Florio Essayes|chapter=16|book=II|passage=''Paulus Emilius'' going to the glorious expedition of ''M"
  body "acedon'', advertised the people of ''Rome'' during his absence not to speake of his actions: ''For the licence of judgements is an especiall '''let''' in great affaires.''}}\n# {{lb|en|tennis}} The [["
  body "hindrance]] caused by the [[net]] during [[serve]], only if the ball falls legally.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|without let or hindrance}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|hindrance}}\n"
  body "* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|obstáculo|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|prepreka}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|hindrance caused by the net during serve at tennis}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|filet|m}}\n* German: "
  body "{{t+|de|Netzball|m}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|tukurua}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===References===\n* [http://www.dsl.ac.uk/entry/dost/let_v The Dictionary of the Scots Language]\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en"
  body "|a=elt|ELT|ETL|LTE|TEL|TLE|Tel.|elt|tel}}\n\n{{cln|en|irregular past participles|irregular simple past forms|irregular verbs}}\n\n==Ahtna==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom or related to {{m|aht|łet||smoke}"
  body "}.\n\n====Root====\n{{head|aht|root}}\n\n# a [[smudge]] or [[smokey]] [[fire]] [[burn]]s\n# to (cause to) burn to [[ash]]es\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|dur|let|l"
  body "et|let|let}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|mom|liit|let|liił|liit}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|conc|let|let|let|let}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|aht\n|dedlet<t:it is smoldering>\n}}\n\"
  body "n====References====\n* {{Kari|page=278}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Root====\n{{head|aht|root}}\n\n# to [[wobble]]\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|mom|let|let|let|l"
  body "et}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|cust|liit|liit|liit|liit}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|aht\n|keghalet<t:it is wobbling>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari|page=277}}\n\n===Et"
  body "ymology 3===\n\n====Root====\n{{head|aht|root}}\n\n# to [[melt]]\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row|mom|laat|let|leł|laat}}\n{{aht-stem-set-row2|prog|{{l|aht|leł}}|—|—|"
  body "—}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|aht\n|cʼghaleł<t:it is melting>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari|page=277}}\n\n==Champenois==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|r"
  body "oa-cha|leuil|leil|q=Rémois}}\n* {{alter|roa-cha|leu|q=Langrois}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|roa-cha|fro|lit}}, from {{inh|roa-cha|la|lectus}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|roa-cha|/lɛ/}}\n\n===Noun"
  body "===\n{{head|roa-cha|noun|g=m|plural|lets}}\n\n# {{lb|roa-cha|Troyen|Langrois}} [[bed]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:roa-cha:Daunay}}\n* {{R:roa-cha:Baudouin}}\n\n==Czech==\n{{wp|cs:}}\n\n===Pronunciatio"
  body "n===\n* {{cs-IPA}}\n* {{audio|cs|Cs-let.ogg}}\n* {{homophones|cs|led}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|cs|sla-pro|*letъ}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{cs-noun|m-in}}\n\n# [[flight]] {{gl|the act of [[flying]]}}\n"
  body "\n=====Declension=====\n{{cs-ndecl|m}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col|cs\n|letět\n|letový\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|cs|noun form|g=n}}\n\n# {{infl of|cs|léto||g"
  body "en|p}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:cs:PSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:SSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:IJP}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|da|gmq-oda|læt}}, from {{inh|da|non|léttr}}, from {{der|da|gem-pro|*lin"
  body "htaz}}. Cognate with {{cog|sv|lätt}}, {{cog|is|léttur}}, {{cog|en|light}}, {{cog|nl|licht}} and {{cog|de|leicht}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈlɛd̥]}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{da-adj||lette}"
  body "}\n\n# [[light]] {{gl|not heavy}}\n# [[easy]]\n# [[slight]]\n# [[mild]]\n\n=====Inflection=====\n{{da-infl-adj|lett|est}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|easy}} {{l|da|nem}}, {{l|da|enkel}}\n\n====Ad"
  body "verb====\n{{head|da|adverb}}\n\n# [[lightly]]\n# [[easily]]\n# [[slightly]]\n# [[mildly]]\n\n====References====\n* {{R:DDO|let,2}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nAbbreviation of {{m|da|letmælk}}.\n\n====Pronun"
  body "ciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈlɛd̥]}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{da-noun|en|stem=lett}}\n\n# [[low-fat]] [[milk]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{da-decl|en|stem=lett}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:DDO|let,1}}\n\n===E"
  body "tymology 3===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈlɛd̥]}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|da|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|da|lette||imp}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Pronunciation"
  body "====\n* {{IPA|da|[ˈleˀd̥]}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|da|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|da|le||past|participle}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-let.ogg}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|ɛt|s=1}}\n\n==="
  body "Verb===\n{{head|nl|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nl|letten||bare-ten-verb}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|nl|tel}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|fr|:bor|en:let}}\n{{bor+|fr|en|let}}.\n\n===Pronuncia"
  body "tion===\n* {{fr-IPA|lète}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Xenophôn-let.wav}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-let.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-let.wav|a=<<F"
  body "rance>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{fr-intj}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|tennis}} {{n-g|indicates a let on service}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n==Friulian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|fu"
  body "r|la|lēctus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|legō}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|fur|verb form}}\n\n# {{past participle of|fur|lei|nocat=1|t=read}}\n\n==Gothic==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{got-rom|head"
  body "=lēt}}\n\n# {{romanization of|got|𐌻𐌴𐍄}}\n\n==Irish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ga|led}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ga|/lʲɛt̪ˠ/}}\n\n===Contraction===\n{{head|ga|contraction|triggers {{g"
  body "a-mut-link|l}}}}\n\n# {{lb|ga|Munster}} {{contraction of|ga|le|do|lit=with your {{g|s}}}}\n#: {{ux|ga|[[le do thoil|'''let''' thoil]]|please|inline=1}}\n\n====Related terms====\n{{ga-preposition contr"
  body "actions}}\n\n==North Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|frr|leet||Föhr-Amrum}}\n* {{alt|frr|lätje||Mooring}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|frr|ofs|lēta}}, from {{inh|frr|gmw-pro|*lātan}}.\n\n="
  body "==Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|frr|[lɛt]}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|frr|verb}}\n\n# {{lb|frr|Sylt}} to {{l|en|let}}\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{frr-Sylt-conj-table|inf_2=leten|ppp=leten|pres_2=letst|pres_3=le"
  body "t|past_1=let|past_2=letst}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{der+|nb|non|litr||colour}}, related to {{m|non|líta||to see}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nb-noun-m1}}\n\n# [[color]] / [[colour]]\n"
  body "\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|nb|farge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nb|hamlet}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nb|verbf}}\n\n# {{infl of|nb|lete||imp}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nb"
  body ":OB}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|nn|non|litr||colour}}, from {{inh|nn|gem-pro|*wlitiz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*wlituz}}. Related to {{cog|non|líta||to see}}.\n\n====Alternative forms"
  body "====\n* {{nn-fcon|2012}} {{alt|nn|lett}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-m2}}\n\n# [[color]] / [[colour]]\n#: {{syn|nn|farge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|nn|einleta}}\n* {{l|nn|hamlet}}\n\n===Etymol"
  body "ogy 2===\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|nn|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|la||pres|tense}}\n# {{infl of|nn|lata||pres}}\n# {{infl of|nn|la||past|tense}}\n# {{infl of|nn|lata||past}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n=="
  body "==Verb====\n{{head|nn|verb form}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|leta||imp}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|nn|a=elt|elt|etl|lèt|lét|tel}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Pronunci"
  body "ation===\n* {{ang-IPA|lēt}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|ang|verb form|head=lēt}}\n\n# {{infl of|ang|lǣtan||1//3|s|pret|indc}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sh|sla-pro|*letъ}}. {{etydate|1"
  body "7th century}}.<ref>{{R:sh:ERHJ|let|547|1}}</ref>\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sh-IPA|lȇt}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sh-noun|lȇt|m-in}}\n\n# [[flight]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|lȇt|létovi\n|lȇta|"
  body "létōvā\n|lȇtu|létovima\n|lȇt|létove\n|lȇte|létovi\n|létu|létovima\n|lȇtom|létovima\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|sh|lèteti}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sh:H"
  body "JP|e19iXxA%3D}}\n\n==Slovene==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|sl|sla-pro|*letъ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sl-IPA|lȅt}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{sl-noun|lȅt|m-in}}\n\n# [[flight]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{sl-d"
  body "ecl-noun-m|lèt|lét}}\n\n==Tok Pisin==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|tpi|en|leather}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|tpi|noun}}\n\n# [[leather]]\n# [[strap]] {{gl|of leather}}\n# [[belt]]""}}"

response_0026_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=living&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""living"",""pageid"":8393,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ˈlɪvɪŋ/}}\n* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-living.wav|a=UK}}\n* {{audi"
  body "o|en|en-us-living.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɪvɪŋ|s=2}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|livynge}}, {{m|enm|libbyng}}, {{m|enm|livinde}}, {{m|enm|livand}}, {{m|enm|livende}}, {{m|enm|libbinde}},"
  body " {{m|enm|libbende}}, from {{inh|en|ang|lifiġende}}, {{m|ang|lifiende}}, {{m|ang|libbende}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*libbjan|*libbjandī}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*libjaną|*libjandz|t=living}}, present pa"
  body "rticiple of {{der|en|gem-pro|*libjaną|t=to live}}, equivalent to {{suf|en|live|-ing|id2=participial}}. Cognate with {{cog|fy|libbend|t=living}}, {{cog|nl|levend|t=living}}, {{cog|de|lebend|t=living}},"
  body " {{cog|sv|levande|t=living}}, {{cog|is|lifandi|t=living}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|en|verb form}}\n\n# {{present participle of|en|live}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj|-}}\n\n# Having [[life]]; [[aliv"
  body "e]].\n#: {{ux|en|a '''living''', breathing child}}\n#: {{ux|en|Respect for the dead does not preclude respect for the '''living'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Schuster Hepaticae|volume=V|page=ix|text=It is also perti"
  body "nent to note that the current obvious decline in work on holarctic hepatics most surely reflects a current obsession with cataloging and with nomenclature of the organisms—as divorced from their study"
  body " as '''living''' entities.}}\n# In use or [[exist]]ing.\n#: {{ux|en|Hunanese is a '''living''' language.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1897|author=Richard Marsh|title=The Beetle\n|passage=The cab pulled "
  body "up in front of a tumbledown cheap ‘villa’ in an unfinished cheap neighbourhood, — the whole place a '''living''' monument of the defeat of the speculative builder.}}\n# [[true to life|True to life]].\"
  body "n#: {{ux|en|This is the '''living''' image of Fidel Castro.}}\n# Of rock or stone, existing in its original state and place.\n#* {{RQ:Haggard She|passage=This we followed for about five paces, when it"
  body " suddenly widened out into a small chamber, about eight feet square, and hewn out of the '''living''' rock.}}\n# Continually updated; not [[static]]\n#: {{ux|en|HTML is a '''living''' standard.}}\n# {"
  body "{non-gloss|Used as an [[intensifier]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|He almost beat the '''living''' daylights out of me.}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|having life}} {{l|en|extant}}, {{l|en|living}}, {{l|en|vita"
  body "l}}; see also [[Thesaurus:alive]]\n* {{sense|existing}} {{l|en|extant}}; See also [[Thesaurus:existent]]\n* {{sense|representing life}} {{l|en|lifey}}, {{l|en|lifelike}}, {{l|en|limned}}, {{l|en|livel"
  body "y}}, {{l|en|naturalistic}}\n* {{sense|intensifier}} {{l|en|blasted}}, {{l|en|doggone}}, {{l|en|stinking}}; see also [[Thesaurus:damned]]\n\n=====Antonyms=====\n* {{l|en|dead}}\n* {{l|en|nonliving}}\n\"
  body "n=====Hyponyms=====\n* {{l|en|long-living}}\n* {{l|en|longest-living}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|living death|not a living soul|living end|living space|living floor|sliving|livingly|everliv"
  body "ing|landliving|livingness|livingry|unliving|living room|high-living|living diaper|living donation|living donor|living thing|living internet theory|living memory|living will|activities of daily living|"
  body "by the living jingo|clean-living|free-living|in living color|in living memory|knock the living daylights out of|living bandage|living constitution|living dead|living fossil|living hell|living hinge|li"
  body "ving impaired|living language|living legend|living mulch|living museum|living picture|living proof|living rock|living sculpture|living statue|living street|living tissue|living tree doctrine|living wa"
  body "ll|non-living|scare the living daylights out of|within living memory|living newspaper|living wage|living stone|living shield|living trust|living fence}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|en|live}}, {{"
  body "l|en|life}}\n* {{l|en|alive}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|having life}}\n* Albanian: {{t|sq|rron}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|حَيّ|m|tr=ḥayy}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|կենդանի}}, {{qualifier|colloquial"
  body ", dialectal}} {{t+|hy|սաղ}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+|az|diri}}, {{t+|az|sağ}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|тере}}\n* Bengali: {{t+|bn|জীবন্ত}}, {{t+|bn|জিন্দা}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|жив}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|viu}}"
  body "\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|vivanta}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|elävä}}, {{t+|fi|elollinen}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|vivant}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|vivo}}\n* German: {{t+|de|lebend}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ζωντανός}}, {{t+|"
  body "el|έμβιος}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ζωός}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|חי|tr=khay}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|जीवित}}, {{t|hi|ज़िंदा}}, {{t+|hi|जीवी}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|lifandi}}\n* Kabuverdianu: {{t|kea|bibu}}"
  body ", {{t|kea|vive}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|살다|alt=산}}, {{t+|ko|살다|alt=살아 있는}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|animalis}}, {{t+|la|vivus}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|kaiao}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|जिवंत}}, {{t|mr|सजीव}}\n* Polish: {{t+|"
  body "pl|żywy}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|vivo}}, {{t+|pt|vivente}}\n* Rapa Nui: {{t|rap|aringa}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|viu|m}}, {{t+|ro|vie|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|живо́й}}, {{t+|ru|жить|alt=живу́щий}}\n* Sans"
  body "krit: {{t+|sa|आयु}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|живети}}, {{t|sh|живјети}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|živeti}}, {{t+|sh|živjeti}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbian: {{t|dsb|žywy}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|"
  body "levande}}\n* Tocharian B: {{t|txb|śāmane}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|живи́й}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|in use or existing}}\n* Albanian: {{t+|sq|ka}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|жив}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi"
  body "|elävä}}\n* Galician: {{t+|gl|vivo|m}}\n* German: {{t+|de|lebend}}, {{t+|de|existent}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ζωντανός}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|קַיָּם|m}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|현존하다|alt=현존하는}}, {{t|ko|현존|alt=현존의}}"
  body ", {{t+|ko|현대|alt=현대의}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|żywy}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|vivo}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|жить|alt=живу́щий}}, {{t+|ru|живо́й}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t|sh|živuća}}\n* Sorbian:\n*: Lower Sorbia"
  body "n: {{t|dsb|žywy}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|levande}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|of everyday life}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|生活}}\n* Dutch: {{t|nl|levens-}}\n* "
  body "Finnish: {{qualifier|in compounds}} {{t+|fi|elin-}}\n* German: {{t|de|Lebens-}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|생활|alt=생활의}}, {{t|ko|거주|alt=거주의}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|życiowy}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|жи́зненный}}\n* Se"
  body "rbo-Croatian: {{t|sh|živući}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|true to life}}\n* Albanian: {{t|sq|përjetuar}}\n* Bashkir: {{t|ba|тормошсан}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|elävä}}\n"
  body "* German: {{t+|de|lebensecht}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|실물|alt=실물 그대로의}}, {{t+|ko|생생하다|alt=생생한}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|жива}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|živa}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|levande}}\n{{tra"
  body "ns-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|used as an intensifier}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|정말}}, {{t+|ko|정말로}}, {{t+|ko|진짜}}, {{t|ko|진짜로}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Interlin"
  body "gua: {{t-check|ia|vive}}, {{t-check|ia|vivente}}\n* Romanian: {{t+check|ro|viu}}\n* Spanish: {{t+check|es|vivo}}, {{t+check|es|viviente}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|livy"
  body "nge}}, {{m|enm|libbynge}}, equivalent to {{suf|en|live|-ing|id2=gerund noun}}. Cognate with {{cog|dum|levinge}}, (whence {{cog|nl|leving|t=way of life, living}}), {{cog|gml|lēvinge|t=living}}.\n\n===="
  body "Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The state of being [[alive]].\n# Financial means; a means of maintaining life; [[livelihood]]\n#: {{collocation|en|it's a '''living'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|"
  body "What do you do for a '''living'''?}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=10 Dec 83|volume=11|number=21|journal=Gay Community News|page=14|author=Jolanta Benal|title=The Second Revolution|text=Career opportuni"
  body "ty {{...}} is the one who never knocks — especially not on the doors of women, who are still hooking, housewifing and hairdressing for their '''livings'''.}}\n# A style of life.\n#: {{ux|en|plain '''l"
  body "iving'''}}\n#: {{ux|en|The National Brewing Company declared that the Chesapeake Bay region was the Land of Pleasant '''Living'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|with \""the\""}} Those who are alive: [[#Adjective|living]"
  body "] people.\n#: {{syn|en|q=archaic|quick#Noun}}\n#: {{ant|en|dead#Noun|;|q2=polite|deceased#Noun|departed#Noun}}\n#: {{collocation|en|in the land of '''the living'''}}\n#: {{collocation|en|Glad to see y"
  body "ou're still among '''the living'''! [good-humored greeting]}}\n#: {{ux|en|Some say that the spirits of the departed walk among '''the living''', though most of us do not see them.}}\n# {{lb|en|canon l"
  body "aw}} A position in a church (usually the Church of England) that has attached to it a source of income; an ecclesiastical [[benefice]].\n#* {{RQ:Spelman De Non Temerandis Ecclesiis|pages=2–3|pageref=2"
  body "|passage=A Rectory or Parſonage, is a ''Spirituall '''liuing''''', compoſed of ''Land'', ''Tythe'', and other ''Oblations'' of the people, ſeparate or dedicate to God in any ''Congregation'', for the "
  body "ſeruice of his Church there, and for the maintenance of the ''Gouernour'' or ''Miniſter'' thereof, to vvhoſe charge the ſame is committed.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2015|author=GR Evans|title=Edward "
  body "Hicks: Pacifist Bishop at War|passage=The patron of the '''living''' who had the right to nominate a particular priest might make the choice, but the '''living''' was actually granted by the local bis"
  body "hop.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col4|en|it takes a heap of living to make a house a home|cost of living|earn a living|it takes a lot of living to make a house a home|land of the living|living cha"
  body "mber|living conditions|living history|living quarters|living standard|living wage|scratch a living|simple living|standard of living\n|make a living|assisted living|sober living house|the world owes on"
  body "e a living\n|coliving|livingless|misliving|what do you do for a living}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|state of being alive}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|yaşayış}}, {{t+|az|həyat}}\n* Bulgarian: {"
  body "{t|bg|живе́ене|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|vivado}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|elo}}, {{t+|fi|eläminen}}, {{t+|fi|elämä}}\n* German: {{t|de|Lebende|f}}, {{t|de|Lebender|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|ζωή|f}}\n* Hindi: {"
  body "{t+|hi|जीवित}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|생존(生存)}}, {{t+|ko|살다|alt=살아 있음}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|iiná}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|życie}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|жизнь|f}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|liv|n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{"
  body "trans-top|financial means; a means of maintaining life}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|مَعِيشَة|f}}, {{t|ar|مَعَاش|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|прехра́на|f}}, {{t+|bg|препита́ние|n}}, {{t|bg|[[средство|средства]] за"
  body " [[преживя́ване]]|n-p}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|生計|tr=shēngjì}}, {{t+|cmn|飯碗|tr=fànwǎn}} {{qualifier|lit.: \""rice bowl\""}}\n* Finnish: {{qualifier|in compounds}} {{t|fi|ansio-}}, {{t+|fi|ty"
  body "ö}}, {{t+|fi|elinkeino}}, {{t+|fi|elanto}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Lebensunterhalt|m}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|επιούσιος|m}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|מִחְיָה|f|tr=miẖyá}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|जीविका|f}}\n* Japanese: {{t+"
  body "|ja|生計|tr=せいけい, seikei}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|생계(生計)}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|victus|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|levebrød|n}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|levebrød|n}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|życie}}, {{t+|pl|utr"
  body "zymanie|n}}, {{t|pl|źródło utrzymania|n}}, {{t|pl|środki do życia|m-p}}\n* Russian: {{t|ru|сре́дства к существова́нию|n-p}}, {{t+|ru|пропита́ние|n}}, {{t+|ru|жизнь|f}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|"
  body "se|ealáhus}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|ganarse la vida}}, {{t+|es|trabajo|m}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|פּרנסה|f|tr=parnose}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|style of life}}\n* Arabic: {{t+|ar|حَيَاة|f}}, {{t|ar|"
  body "طَرِيقَة فِي حَيَاة|f|tr=ṭarīqa fī ḥayāh}}, {{t|ar|نَمَط حَيَاة|m}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t|az|yaşayış}}, {{t+|az|həyat}}, {{t|az|yaşayış tərzi}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|на́чин на живо́т|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: "
  body "Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|生活方式|tr=shēnghuó fāngshì}}, {{t+|cmn|生態|tr=shēngtài}}, {{t+|cmn|方式|tr=fāngshì}}, {{t+|cmn|生活|tr=shēnghuó}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|elämä}}, {{t+|fi|elintapa}}, {{t+|fi|elo}}, {{t+|fi|el"
  body "ämäntapa}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|mode de vie|f}}, {{t+|fr|vie|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Leben|n}}, {{t+|de|Lebensumstände|f}}, {{t+|de|Lebensweise|f}}, {{t+|de|Lebensstil|m}}\n* Hindi: {{t|hi|जीवनशैली|f}}\n"
  body "* Japanese: {{t+|ja|生活様式|tr=せいかつようしき, seikatsu yōshiki}}, {{t+|ja|暮らし|tr=くらし, kurashi}}, {{t+|ja|生活|tr=せいかつ, seikatsu}}\n* Korean: {{t|ko|생활방식(生活方式)}}, {{t+|ko|생활양식(生活樣式)}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|życie}}\"
  body "n* Russian: {{t+|ru|о́браз жи́зни|m}}, {{t+|ru|стиль жи́зни|m}}, {{t+|ru|жизнь|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|estilo de vida|m}}\n* Tagalog: {{t|tl|pamumuhay}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|those who are a"
  body "live}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|живите|p}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|superī|m-p}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|(canon law) a position in a church attached to a source of income}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}"
  body "\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{cln|en|intensifiers}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|nl|fr|living}} or, less plausibly, an independent truncated borrowing from {{bor|nl|en|living room}}."
  body "\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/ˈlɪ.vɪŋ/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-living.ogg}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|ɪvɪŋ|s=2}}\n* {{hyphenation|nl|li|ving}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nl-noun|m|-s|-}}\n\n# {{lb|nl|Belgium}} [[living "
  body "room]]\n#: {{syn|nl|huiskamer|woonkamer}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|fr|:bor|en:living room<alt:living (room)>}}\n{{bor+|fr|en|living room|living (room)}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-"
  body "IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Jérémy-Günther-Heinz Jähnick-living.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Somain>>)}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# [[living room]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n{{C"
  body "|fr|Rooms}}\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{pseudo-loan|it|en}}, a clipping of {{der|it|en|living room}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|m}}\n\n# [[living room]]\n#: {{syn|it|soggiorno}}\n\n==Romanian="
  body "=\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|ro|en|living-room}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{ro-noun|n|livinguri}}\n\n# [[living room]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{ro-noun-n-uri}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ubor|es|en|l"
  body "iving room|living (room)}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{es-pr|livin}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{lb|es|Rioplatense|Chile}} [[living room]]\n#: {{syn|es|sala de estar}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n{"
  body "{es-unadapted}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}\n* {{R:es:DA}}\n\n{{C|es|Rooms}}""}}"

response_0027_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=loaf&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""loaf"",""pageid"":54711,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""==English==\n[[Image:Breads.jpg|thumb|Two loaves (1) of [[bread]]]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ləʊf/|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|L"
  body "L-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-loaf.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/loʊf/|a=GenAm}}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊf|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=block of bread|:inh|enm:lof<id:loaf>|tree=1}}\n* From {{"
  body "inh|en|enm|laf}}, {{m|enm|lof}}, {{m|enm|loof}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hlāf|t=bread; loaf}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hlaib}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hlaibaz|t=bread; loaf}}, of {{unc|en|nocap=1}} origin. P"
  body "erhaps related to {{cog|ang|hlifian|t=to stand out prominently, tower up}}. \n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|de|Laib|t=loaf}}, {{cog|da,sv|lev|t=loaf}}, {{cog|fo|leivur|t=an oblong bun}}, {{cog"
  body "|is|hleifur|t=loaf}}, {{cog|nn|leiv|t=loaf}}, {{cog|got|𐌷𐌻𐌰𐌹𐌱𐍃}}, {{m|got|𐌷𐌻𐌰𐌹𐍆𐍃|t=bread}} (whence {{cog|sla-pro|*xlěbъ|t=bread}} (see there for further descendants)), {{cog|et|leib|t=black bread}}, {"
  body "{cog|fi|leipä|t=bread; loaf}}; also {{cog|lv|klaips|t=loaf}}, {{cog|lt|kliẽpas|t=loaf}}. {{doublet|en|chleb|khleb}}.\n* {{sense|brain or head}} Rhyming slang, {{ellipsis|en|loaf of bread|nocap=1}}.\n{"
  body "{col-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|loaves}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|bread}} {{q|also {{m|en|loaf of bread}}}} A [[block]] of [[bread]] after [[bake|baking]].\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter="
  body "8|passage=Philander went into the next room{{...}}and came back with a salt mackerel that dripped brine like a rainstorm. Then he put the coffee pot on the stove and rummaged out a '''loaf''' of dry b"
  body "read and some hardtack.}}\n# Any [[solid]] block of [[food]], such as [[meat]] or [[sugar]].\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Sylva Sylvarum|4|passage=sugar-'''loaf'''}}\n# {{lb|en|Cockney rhyming slang}} {{ellipsis of"
  body "|en|loaf of bread}}: the [[brain]] or the [[head]].<ref>{{R:GDoS|id=lueucni|entry=loaf (of bread)|pos=n}}</ref>\n#: {{syn|en|q=slang|bonce|noddle|nut|Thesaurus:head}}\n#: {{co|en|[[use one's loaf|use "
  body "one's '''loaf''']]}}\n#* {{RQ:Wodehouse Jeeves in the Offing|chapter=VIII and XII|passage=It is frequently said of Bertram Wooster that he is a man who can think on his feet, and if the necessity aris"
  body "es he can also use his '''loaf<!--(as \""brain\"")-->''' when on all fours. [...]<!--ch. XII--> “Why didn't the idiot tell her not to open it?” “It was his first move. ‘I've found a letter from you here"
  body ", precious,’ she said. ‘On no account open it, angel,’ he said. So of course she opened it.” She pursed the lips, nodded the '''loaf<!--(as \""head\"")-->''', and ate a moody piece of crumpet. “So that'"
  body "s why he's been going about looking like a dead fish.”}}\n# A solid block of [[soap]], from which standard [[bar soap]] is [[cut]].\n# {{lb|en|cellular automata}} A particular [[still life]] configura"
  body "tion with seven living [[cell]]s.\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=1989-11-20|author=Dean Hickerson|title=Life: glider gun origin|newsgroup=comp.theory.cell-automata|url=https://groups.google.com/g/comp."
  body "theory.cell-automata/c/kL6pRsRDG4Q/m/jyweN_cOzTgJ|text=It runs for 17331 generations before stabilizing as 136 blinkers, 109 blocks, 65 beehives, 18 '''loaves''', 18 boats, 7 ships, 4 tubs, 3 ponds, 2"
  body " toads, and 40 gliders.}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=1992-09-10|author=David Bell|title=Spaceships in Conway's Life (Part 3b)|newsgroup=comp.theory.cell-automata|url=https://groups.google.com/g/com"
  body "p.theory.cell-automata/c/WNVmyQYN0EQ/m/LJulQ32mFWcJ|text=Running a LWSS into it can produce various debris. One of these reactions produces a '''loaf'''. When the '''loaf''' is properly hit with other"
  body " LWSSs, it can be pulled backwards.}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=1998-01-27|author=Ian Osgood|title=Life: looking for smallest ancestor of a quad-loaf|newsgroup=comp.theory.cell-automata|url=https:"
  body "//groups.google.com/g/comp.theory.cell-automata/c/jAV2m1Ds86E/m/chr7Ia-PjYcJ|text=I am looking for the smallest ancestor of the following four '''loaf''' pattern in Conway's Game of Life:}}\n# {{lb|en"
  body "|informal|slang}} A [[catloaf]].\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|barracouta loaf\n|catloaf\n|catloafed\n|confinement loaf\n|cottage loaf\n|disciplinary loaf\n|Dutch loaf\n|farmhouse loaf\n|farthi"
  body "ng loaf\n|flesh loaf\n|fleshloaf\n|foodloaf\n|French loaf\n|frosted ribbon loaf\n|granary loaf\n|half a loaf is better than no bread\n|half a loaf is better than no loaf\n|half a loaf is better than n"
  body "one\n|liverloaf\n|loaf bread\n|loaflet\n|loaflike\n|loaf of bread\n|loaf pan\n|loaf sugar\n|malt loaf\n|meatless loaf\n|meatloaf,meat loaf\n|nut loaf\n|olive loaf\n|pan-loaf\n|pimento loaf\n|pinch a l"
  body "oaf\n|plain loaf\n|Pullman loaf\n|ribbon loaf\n|sandwich loaf\n|sugar loaf,sugar-loaf\n|tank loaf\n|tea loaf\n|temse loaf\n|Vienna loaf\n|wave loaf\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|bn|"
  body "লোফ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|mh|ļoob|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nb|loff|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nn|loff|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|gd|lofa|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|block of bread}}\n* Arabic: {{t|a"
  body "r|رَغِيف|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|самун|m}}, {{t+|bg|хляб|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|fogassa|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|一條麵包|tr=yī tiáo miànbāo}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|torth|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+|c"
  body "s|bochník|m}}, {{t+|cs|pecen|m}}\n*: Old Czech: {{t|zlw-ocs|bochnec|m}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|brood|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+check|eo|bulo}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|päts}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|leipä}}, {{t+|fi|li"
  body "mppu}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|baguette|f}}, {{t+|fr|miche|f}}, {{t+|fr|pain|m}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|bolo|m}}, {{t|gl|molete|m}}, {{t|gl|sembra|f}}, {{t|gl|panocha|f}}, {{t|gl|tarxa|f}}, {{t|gl|regueifa|f}"
  body "}, {{t|gl|fogaza|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ბატონი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Laib|m}}, {{t|de|Laib Brot|m}}, {{t+|de|Brot|n}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|καρβέλι|n}}, {{t+|el|φρατζόλα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἄρτ"
  body "ος|m}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|pōpō}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|כיכר|tr=kikár}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|kenyér}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|hleifur|m}}, {{t+|is|brauð|n}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|bulkka}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|b"
  body "airín|m}}, {{t|ga|bollóg|f}}, {{t|ga|builín|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pagnotta|f}}, {{t|it|pan carrè|m}}, {{t|it|pane in cassetta|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[パン]][[一]][[塊]]|tr=pan hito katamari}}, {{t|ja|"
  body "[[パン]][[一]][[斤]]|tr=pan ikkin}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|бөлке}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|pānis|m}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|kukulis}}, {{t+|lv|klaips|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|ве́кна|f}}, {{t|mk|сому́н|m}}\n* Malay: {{t"
  body "+|ms|buku}}\n* Māori: {{t-check|mi|rohi}}\n* Old Church Slavonic: {{t|cu|хлѣбъ|m}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|bochenek|m}}, {{t+|pl|bochen|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pão|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|pâine|f}}, {{"
  body "t+|ro|franzelă|f}}, {{t+|ro|jimblă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|буха́нка|f}}, {{t+|ru|бу́лка|f}}, {{t+|ru|бато́н|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|lof|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|вѐкна|f}}, {{"
  body "t|sh|векница|f}}, {{t|sh|хле̏б|m}}, {{t|sh|хље̏б|m}}, {{t|sh|штру̏ца|f}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|vèkna|f}}, {{t+|sh|veknica|f}}, {{t+|sh|hlȅb|m}}, {{t+|sh|hljȅb|m}}, {{t+|sh|štrȕca|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t|sl|h"
  body "leb|m}}, {{t|sl|hlebec|m}}, {{t|sl|štruca|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pan|m}}, {{t+|es|hogaza|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|mkate|c3|c4}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|limpa|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t-needed|tl}}\n* Taos: {{t|t"
  body "wf|pʼȍkúna}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|torth|f}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|לעבל|n}}, {{t|yi|לאַבן|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|block of food}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|torth|f}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|päts}}, {{t|et|"
  body "latt}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|mureke}} {{qualifier|minced meat}}; {{t+|fi|toppa}} {{qualifier|sugar}}, {{t+|fi|kimpale}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t-needed|haw}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|hleifur|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es"
  body "|pan|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|head (''slang'')}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|testa|f}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|kupp}}, {{t+|et|kaalikas}}, {{t+|et|nupp}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|polla}}\n* Italian: {{t|it"
  body "|capoccia|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|коча́н|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|mollera|f}}, {{t+|es|testa|f}} {{qualifier|slang}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|large block of soap}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|barra|f}}"
  body "\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|tanko}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|savonnette|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|panetto|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|barra|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|barra|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====References=====\"
  body "n<references/>\n* (soap) Miller, J.L. \""Customers believe in downstate Soap Fairy\"", ''[[Wikipedia:Delaware News-Journal|The News Journal]]'', B10, January 10, 2006.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# "
  body "{{lb|en|Cockney rhyming slang}} To [[headbutt]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nProbably a {{back-form|en|loafer|nocap=3}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To do nothing, to be [[idle]]"
  body ".\n#: {{ux|en|'''loaf''' about, '''loaf''' around}}\n#* '''2015,''' {{w|Elizabeth Royte}}, ''Vultures Are Revolting. Here’s Why We Need to Save Them.'', National Geographic (December 2015)[https://web"
  body ".archive.org/web/20151213095110/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2016/01/vultures-text]\n#*: They don’t (often) kill other animals, they probably form monogamous pairs, and we know they share parenta"
  body "l care of chicks, and '''loaf''' and bathe in large, congenial groups.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|en|idle}}, {{l|en|laze}}, {{l|en|lounge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|loaf about|loaf arou"
  body "nd}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|nn|loffe|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sv|luffa|bor=1}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|do nothing}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|безделнича}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|ganduleja"
  body "r}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎡᏙᎵᏙᎭ}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|zahálet}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|niksen}}, {{t+|nl|rondlummelen}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|logelema}}, {{t|et|laisklema}}, {{t|et|vedelema}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|f"
  body "i|maleksia}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|paresser}}\n* German: {{t|de|nichts tun}}, {{t+|de|herumlungern}}, {{t|de|rumhängen}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|de|faulenzen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|τεμπελιάζω}}, {{t+"
  body "|el|κοπροσκυλιάζω}}, {{t+|el|λουφάρω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ῥαθυμέω}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|slóra}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|[[bheith]] [[ag]] [[leadaíocht]] ([[thart]])}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|oziare}}, "
  body "{{t+|it|bighellare}}, {{t+|it|girovagare}}, {{t+|it|vagabondare}}, {{t|it|trastullarsi}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|slaistīties}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|де́нгуби}}, {{t|mk|безде́лничи}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|ānewan"
  body "ewa}}, {{t|mi|kaweka}}, {{t|mi|whakapāeko}}, {{t|mi|whakapateko}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|bimbać|impf}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|pl|przebimbać|pf}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|vad"
  body "iar}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|trândăvi}}, {{t+|ro|lenevi}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|бездельничать|impf}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|holgazanear}}, {{t|es|estar a la bartola}}, {{t+|es|golfear}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottom"
  body "an Turkish: {{t|ota|تنبللنمك|tr=tembellenmek}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|diogi}}, {{t+|cy|stelcian}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aflo|AFOL|Olaf|foal}}\n\n{{cln|en|nouns with irregula"
  body "r plurals}}\n{{C|en|Cats|Food and drink}}""}}"

response_0028_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=no&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""no"",""pageid"":465945,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""{{also|Appendix:Variations of \""no\""}}\n{{minitoc}}\n==Translingual==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{clip|mul|en:'''No'''rwegian,no:'''no'''rsk"
  body "}}.\n\n===Symbol===\n{{mul-symbol}}\n\n# {{ISO 639|1}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{langcat}}\n\n==English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{a|en|UK}}\n** {{IPA|en|/nəʊ/|a=RP}}\n*** {{audio|en|en-uk-no.ogg}}\n*"
  body "* {{IPA|en|/no/|a=Scotland}}\n** {{IPA|en|/noː/|a=Wales,non-toe-tow}}\n** {{a|en|Northumbrian}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/niː/|a=determiner, adverb}}\n**** {{IPA|en|/neː/|a=sometimes}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/næ/|/nɜː/|/"
  body "nɑː/|a=particle, noun}}\n* {{IPA|en|/noʊ/|a=GA,CA}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-no.ogg}}\n* {{IPA|en|/nəʉ/|a=AU}}\n* {{IPA|en|/nɐʉ/|a=NZ}}\n** {{audio|en|en-nz-no.ogg}}\n* {{IPA|en|/nœʊ/|a=South Africa}}\n* "
  body "{{rhymes|en|əʊ|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|en|noh|;|know<aa:toe-tow>}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|en|enm|no}}, {{m|enm|noo}}, {{m|enm|na}}, a reduced form of {{m|enm|none}}, {{m|enm|noon}}, {{m|enm|nan||n"
  body "one, not any}} used before consonants (compare {{m|en|a}} to {{m|en|an}}), from {{inh|en|ang|nān|t=none, not any}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*nain}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*nainaz|t=not any|lit=not one}}"
  body ", equivalent to {{com|en|ne|t1=not|a}}. {{piecewise doublet|en|none}}.\n\nCognate with {{cog|sco|nae||no, not any, none}}, {{cog|ofs|nān}}, {{m|ofs|nēn}} {{gloss|\""no, not any, none\""}}, {{cog|stq|naa"
  body "n}}, {{m|stq|neen||no, not any, none}}, {{cog|frr|nian||no, not any, none}}, {{cog|odt|nēn}} {{gloss|\""no, not any, none\""; > {{cog|nl|neen||no}}}}, {{cog|non|neinn||no, not any, none}}. Compare also "
  body "{{cog|osx|nigēn}} {{gloss|\""not any\""; > {{cog|nds|nen}}}}, {{cog|odt|nehēn}} ({{cog|dum|negheen}}/{{m|dum|negeen}}, {{cog|nl|geen}}), {{cog|fy|gjin}}, {{cog|goh|nihein}} (> {{cog|de|kein}}). More at "
  body "''[[no#Etymology_2|no]]'', {{m|en|one}}.\n\n====Determiner====\n{{en-head|det}}\n\n# Not any.\n#: {{syn|en|zero#Determiner|not even one#Determiner|not one#Determiner}}\n#: {{ant|en|any#Determiner|some"
  body "#Determiner|;|one#Determiner|;|a few#Determiner|a [[couple#English:_small number|couple]] of|a [[handful#English:_small number|handful]] of|;|multiple#Determiner|various#Determiner|;|many#Determiner|n"
  body "umerous#Determiner|;|countless#Determiner|every single#Determiner}}\n#: {{ux|en|[[no one|'''no''' one]]}}\n#: {{ux|en|There is '''no''' water left.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''' hot dogs were sold yesterday."
  body "}}\n#: {{ux|en|I've got '''no''' wife and '''no''' children either.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''' two people are the same.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There was '''no''' score at the end of the first period. (The score wa"
  body "s 0-0.)}}\n# [[hardly|Hardly]] any.\n#: {{ant|en|quite|some}}\n#: {{ux|en|We'll be finished in '''no''' time at all.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Fifty pounds for this is '''no''' money, really.}}\n# Not any possibi"
  body "lity or allowance of (something).\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''' smoking. '''No''' parking.}}\n#: {{ux|en|There's '''no''' stopping her once she gets going.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''' [[under-]][[18s]] ([[allowed]]"
  body ").}}\n# Not (a); not properly, not really; not fully.\n#: {{ux|en|My mother's '''no''' fool.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Working nine to five every day is '''no''' life.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''' geese have blue beaks"
  body ".}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|natheless|no clue|no-brow|no-hoper|no-legged|no-platform|no-scope|Nobama|nobbut|nocoiner|nogoer|nohow|nojito|nolisting|noman|noone|nopony|nosecco|noshore|NoSQL"
  body "|nothing|NOTP|novid|noway|nowhat|nowhen|nowhence|nowhile|nowhither|nowise|all fur and no knickers|all retch and no vomit|certificate of no criminal conviction|duck or no dinner|no bigs|no good ass|no "
  body "soup for you|no-stride\n|a closed mouth catches no flies|no later than|no-action letter\n|a closed mouth gathers no feet|no-self|waste no time\n|a little bit of bread and no cheese\n|no-account|no fal"
  body "l zone|no nothing|vote blue no matter who\n|no-brainer|no-show sock| have no right|no brown in town|no fidelity|no need|no-fi\n|no-fault\n|no flies on\n|no-fly\n|no glove no love\n|no-go\n|no-good\n|n"
  body "o guts, no glory\n|no harm, no foul\n|no-hit\n|no-hitter\n|no holds barred\n|no-load\n|no love lost\n|No Man's Heath\n|no man's land\n|No Man's Land\n|no-name\n|no names, no pack drill\n|no news is go"
  body "od news\n|no-no\n|no-nonsense\n|no one,no-one\n|no pain, no gain\n|no place,noplace\n|No Place\n|no problem\n|no quarter\n|no questions asked\n|no rest for the wicked\n|no room at the inn\n|no-score d"
  body "raw\n|no-see-um\n|no shit, Sherlock\n|no-show\n|no skin off one's back\n|no soap|no relation|no trumps|no 🧢|no-trumper\n|no strings attached\n|no through road\n|no-trade\n|no-trump\n|no way to treat a"
  body " lady\n|no-win\n|no wonder\n|no worries\n|say no more\n|be no match for\n|no match for}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Determiner}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{inh+|en|enm|no}}, {{m"
  body "|enm|na}}, from {{inh|en|ang|nā}}, {{m|ang|nō|t=no, not, not ever, never}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*naiwō}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*naiwô|t=never}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*ne|t=not}} + {{m|gem-pro|*aiwō|t=e"
  body "ver}}, equivalent to {{cog|ang|ne}} + {{m|ang|ā}}, {{m|ang|ō}}. Cognate with {{cog|sco|na||no}}, {{cog|stq|noa||no}}, {{cog|fy|né|t=no}}, {{m|fy|nea||never}}, {{cog|nl|nee||no}}, {{cog|nds|nee||no}}, "
  body "{{cog|de|nie||never}}, dialectal {{cog|de|nö|t=no}}, {{cog|da|nej||no}}, {{cog|sv|nej||no}}, {{cog|is|nei||no}}. More at {{m|en|nay}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|with following adjec"
  body "tive}} [[not|Not]], not at all.\n## {{n-g|Used before ''[[different]]'', before comparatives with {{m|en|more}} and {{m|en|less}}, and idiomatically before other comparatives.}}\n##: {{ux|en|It is a l"
  body "ess physical kind of torture, but '''no''' less gruesome.}}\n##: {{ux|en|I can think of '''no''' more deserving cause.}}\n##: {{ux|en|Look '''no''' further than one's nose.}}\n##: {{ux|en|This is '''n"
  body "o''' different from what we've been doing all along.}}\n##: {{ux|en|Is your sister any better? ~ '''No''' different. Still ill.}}\n## {{lb|en|informal}} {{n-g|Used idiomatically before certain other a"
  body "djectives.}}\n##: {{ux|en|This thing is '''no''' good.}}\n##: {{ux|en|The teacher’s decision was '''no''' fair.}}\n# {{lb|en|without adjective|now|Scotland|informal}} [[not|Not]].\n#: {{ux|en|I just w"
  body "ant to find out whether she's coming or '''no'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Can [[ye]] '''no''' help me?}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1725|author=w:Daniel Defoe|title=An essay on the history and reality of appariti"
  body "ons\n|passage=AS the ''Devil'' is not so Black as he is Painted, so neither does he appear in so many Shapes as we make for him; we Dress him up in more Suits of Cloaths, and more Masquerade Habits, t"
  body "han ever he wore; and I question much, if he was to see the Pictures and Figures which we call ''Devil'', whether he would know himself by some of them or '''no'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial|usually|hum"
  body "orous}} Not, does not, do not, etc.\n#: {{ux|en|[[Ug]] '''no''' like veggie.}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\n* When used humorously to mean {{m-g|not}} or {{m-g|does not}}, this word usually implies a [[c"
  body "aveman]]-like way of speaking.\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|no}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{en-head|pcl}}\n\n# {{ng|Used to show [[disagreement]], [[negat"
  body "ion]], [[denial]], [[refusal]], or [[prohibition]].}}\n#: {{syn|en|nay|nope|Thesaurus:no}}\n#: {{ant|en|aye|maybe|yea|yes|Thesaurus:yes}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''', you are mistaken.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No'''"
  body ", you may not watch television now.}}\n#: {{ux|en|David, '''no!'''}}\n# {{ng|Used to express [[sadness]] or [[disappointment]].}}\n#: {{ux|en|We lost. / '''No'''!}}\n# {{ng|Used to express [[disbelief"
  body "]].}}\n#: {{syn|en|no way}}\n#: {{ux|en|I got the job! / '''No'''! Really? That's fantastic!}}\n# {{ng|Used to show [[agreement]] with a [[negative]] [[question]].}}\n#: {{syn|en|nah|nay|nope}}\n#: {{"
  body "ux|en|\""Don’t you like milk?\"" \""'''No'''.\"" (i.e., \""No, I don’t like milk.\"")}}\n# {{lb|en|colloquial}} {{ng|Used together with an [[affirmative]] word or phrase to show [[agreement]].}}\n#: {{ux|en"
  body "|'''No''', totally.}}\n#: {{ux|en|'''No''', yeah, that's exactly right.}}\n#: {{ux|en|\""Wow!\"" \""Yeah, '''no''', it was really awful!\""}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|nossuh|yeah, no|yes and "
  body "no}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|ase|H^o@Side-PalmForward Flatten|bor=1}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Particle}}\n\n====Preposition====\n{{en-head|prep}}\n\n# [[without"
  body "|Without]].\n#: {{usex|en|[[look Ma, no hands|Look Ma, '''no''' hands!]]}}\n# {{rfv-sense|en}} [[like|Like]].\n\n====Noun====\n{{anchor|English-Noun}}\n{{en-noun|es|s}}\n\n# A [[negate|negating]] [[ex"
  body "pression]]; an answer that shows [[disagreement]], [[denial]], [[refusal]], or [[disapproval]].\n#* {{quote-av|en|year=1994|actor=John de Lancie|episode=All Good Things...|title=Star Trek: The Next Ge"
  body "neration|writers=Brannon Braga; Ronald D. Moore|season=7|number=25-26|text=''Q'': I'll answer any ten questions that call for a yes or a '''no'''.}}\n# A [[vote]] not in favor, or opposing a [[proposi"
  body "tion]].\n#: {{ux|en|The workers voted on whether to strike, and there were thirty yeses and two '''nos'''.}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|en|nah}}\n* {{l|en|nope}}\n* {{l|en|naw}}\n* {{l|en|nay}}\n\n="
  body "====Antonyms=====\n* {{l|en|aye}}\n* {{l|en|yea}}\n* {{l|en|yes}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb|~es}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|colloquial}} To"
  body " [[say]] {{m-g|no}}.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1983|author=Sasha Moorsom|chapter=5|title=In the Shadow of the Paradise Tree|location=London&#59; Melbourne, Vic.&#59; Henley-on-Thame, Oxfordshire|publis"
  body "her=[[w:Routledge|Routledge & Kegan Paul]]|page=80|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/inshadowofparadi0000moor/page/80/mode/1up|isbn=0-7100-9408-6|passage=She felt disquiet at these tales of Musa’s i"
  body "llicit activities. ‘Does your father know?’ / ‘My father always '''noes'''. He never yeses. Specially when he’s sick, then he '''noes''' all the time. I gotta get out. Can’t stick around the house wit"
  body "h him yelling.{{nb...}}’}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1994|author=Malcolm Ross|chapter=Part Three: The New Woman|title=Kernow & Daughter|location=London|publisher=[[w:Book Club Associates|BCA]]|page=293"
  body "|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/kernowdaughter0000ross/page/293/mode/1up|isbn=9780749902629|passage=“Heaven knows why a woman ‘'''Noes'''’!” / Clarrie nodded glumly. “And why she ‘Yesses’ in the "
  body "end.”}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2001|author=Nicholas Weinstock|chapter=The Flowers|title=As Long As She Needs Me|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Harper Perennial|Perennial]]|year_published=2002"
  body "|page=140|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=E-eDKUgKBNMC&pg=PA140|isbn=0-06-019824-9|passage=There were days, entire years of his life, spent yessing and '''noing''' on the phone, picking up a"
  body "nd hanging up and accomplishing nothing at all.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|colloquial}} To [[answer]] with {{m-g|no}}; to [[decline]], [[reject]].\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1835|month=April|title=The W"
  body "himsey Papers.—No. II. Vague Conclusions Concerning Selfishness and Benevolence—Vivid the Casuist—Skinflint the Misanthrope—Green, the Good-Natured Man.|editor={{quote-gloss|{{w|Caroline Norton}}}}|jo"
  body "urnal=[[w:La Belle Assemblée|The Court Magazine,]]{{nb...|Containing Original Papers, by Distinguished Writers, and Finely Engraved Portraits, Landscapes, and Costumes, from Paintings by Eminent Maste"
  body "rs.}}|volume=VI|issue=IV|location=London|publisher=Edward Churton,{{nb...|Holles Street, Cavendish Square. (Late Bull and Churton.)}}|page=168|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/courtmagazinean00crit"
  body "goog/page/n190/mode/1up|column=1|oclc=265367566|passage=Never accustom yourself to say ‘Yes,’—practise an emphatic and decisive enunciation of the far more dignified and important monosyllable, ‘No.’ "
  body "{{...}} Believe me, it is of the utmost importance (the advice is not of recent date) that you should '''''No''''' the world.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=17 March 1940|title=Back of the CAA Fight: I"
  body "ndependence or Closer Executive Control of Aviation Agency|editor=[[w:David Lawrence (publisher)|David Lawrence]]|journal=[[w:U.S. News & World Report|The United States News]]|location=Washington, D.C"
  body ".|publisher=United States News Publishing Corporation|page=33|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/sim_u-s-news-weekly-special-issues_1940-05-17_8_20/page/33/mode/1up|column=2|issn=2834-4936|oclc=24368"
  body "43|passage=BUDGET DIRECTOR SMITH / The President yessed his report {{...}} SENATOR McCARRAN / He '''noed''' the President’s report}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1955|author=w:Fred Rodell|chapter=Powerful"
  body ", Irresponsible, and Human|title=Nine Men: A Political History of the Supreme Court from 1790 to 1955|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:Random House|page=12|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/ninem"
  body "enpolitical1955rode/page/12/mode/1up|lccn=55-8154|oclc=345501|passage=Yet in every such instance—and there are scores of them—the Justices can do nothing but impotently point toward future action afte"
  body "r Yessing or '''Noing''' past action by men in a position to act.}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nVariant of {{m|en|No.}}, from the scribal abbreviation for {{bor|en|la|''(''[[in]]'')'' [[numerō]]||[[in]] [[n"
  body "umber]], to the [[number]] of}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{en-adv|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|archaic}} {{alt form|en|No.}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{alt form|en|No.}}\n\n===See also===\n* [[Thesaurus:quant"
  body "ifier]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia|''yes'' and ''no''}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=no|-on|ON|ON.|on|on-}}\n\n{{cln|en|phrasebook|responses|2-let"
  body "ter words}}\n\n==Achang==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|acn|sit-pro|*r-nəʔ|t=ear}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{acn-IPA}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|acn|noun}}\n\n# [[ear]]\n#* {{RQ:acn:Bible|Psalm|"
  body "115|6|'''No''' dap laus eq ma xauhgyo, nho dap laus eq ma yoh nam.|[The idols have] '''ears''' stuck [to them] but do not hear; [the idols have] noses stuck [to them] but cannot smell.|url=https://www"
  body ".bible.com/bible/373/psa.115.6}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nInglis's lexicon does not have this simple word for \""ear\"", despite listing several compounds. The simple word ''does'' show up in his preli"
  body "minary phonology and is attested in the Bible.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|acn\n|no-khyung\n|no-jet\n|no-khung\n|no-khyvp\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|acn|tbq-lob-pro|*na²}}, from {{inh|"
  body "acn|sit-pro|*na|t=to rest}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{acn-IPA\n|lh=na³¹\n|lx=na⁵¹\n|lc=nɔ³¹\n|xd=nɔ³¹\n}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{head|acn|verb}}\n\n# to [[rest]], [[stop]]\n\n===Further reading===\n*"
  body " {{R:acn:Lexicon|93-94}}\n\n==Ainu==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ain-IPA|nó}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Particle====\n{{ain-part|l|{{ain-kana-conv}}}}\n\n# {{n-g|Adverbialising particle}}; [[-ly]], "
  body "[[ing]]\n#: {{ux|ain|[[asiri]]|t=new|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|asiri '''no'''|t=newly|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|[[pirika]]|t=good|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|pirika '''no'''|t=well|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|[[n"
  body "ukara]]|t=to see|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|nukara '''no''' an|t=seeing|lit=being seeing|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|[[opitta]]|t=all|inline=1}}\n#: {{ux|ain|opitta '''no''' okay|t=all|lit=being all|inline=1"
  body "}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Particle====\n{{ain-part|l|{{ain-kana-conv}}}}\n\n# {{alt form|ain|ro}}\n\n==Alemannic German==\n\n===Etymology===\nRelated to {{cog|de|noch}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n*"
  body " {{IPA|gsw|/ˈnɔ/|a=Zurich}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|gsw|adverbs}}\n\n# [[still]], [[yet]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|gsw|Bisch '''no''' do?|Are you '''still''' here?}}\n# [[eventually]] {{gloss|at an unknown t"
  body "ime in the future}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|gsw|Er chunt scho '''no'''.|He will come '''eventually'''.}}\n# (only) just; barely {{gloss|by a small margin}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|gsw|Sii hät grad '''no''' so gwu"
  body "nne.|She '''just barely''' won.}}\n# {{lb|gsw|with comparative}} [[even]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|gsw|Das isch sogar '''no''' schönner.|This is '''even''' prettier.}}\n\n====Usage notes====\n* {{sense|event"
  body "ually}} Often used together with an antecedent {{m|gsw|scho}}.\n* {{sense|just; barely}} In this sense always used together with an antecedent {{m|gsw|grad}}.\n* {{sense|even}} It can be used together"
  body " with an antecedent {{m|gsw|sogar}} for amplification.\n\n===Particle===\n{{head|gsw|particles}}\n\n# {{rfdef|gsw}}\n\n==Ashkun==\n{{cardinalbox|ask|8|9|10|ōṣṭ|dos}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|ask|iir"
  body "-nur-pro|*no}} (or less likely borrowed from a descendant of {{der|ask|sa|नव|tr=náva}}), from {{inh|ask|iir-pro|*Hnáwa}}, from {{inh|ask|ine-pro|*h₁néwn̥}}.\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|ask|numeral}} {{q|"
  body "Sanu}}<ref name=\""NEL\"">{{R:iir-nur:NEL|n′o}}</ref>\n\n# [[nine]]\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n==Asturian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom a contraction of the preposition {{m|ast|en||in}} + neute"
  body "r singular article {{m|ast|lo||the}}. Compare {{cog|scn|ntô}}~{{m|scn|nnô}}.\n\n===Contraction===\n{{head|ast|contraction|g=n|masculine|nel|feminine|na|masculine plural|nos|feminine plural|nes}}\n\n# "
  body "[[in]] [[the]]\n\n==Atong (India)==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|aot|/no/}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n\n====Verb====\n{{aot-verb|নো}}\n\n# to [[say]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{bor+|aot|hi|नौ}}.\n\n====Nu"
  body "meral====\n{{aot-num|নো}}\n\n# [[nine]]\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|aot|chykhyw}}\n* {{l|aot|nain}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:aot:Breugel}} For \""nine\"", stated in Appendix 3.\n\n==Awa (New Guinea)="
  body "=\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|awb|nouns}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* ''The Papuan Languages of New Guinea'' (1986, {{ISBN|0521286212}}\n\n==Bangi==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|bni|bnt-pro|*-nók}}."
  body "\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|bni|verb}}\n\n# to [[fall]] (rain), to [[rain]]\n\n==Bavarian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|bar|goh|noh}}, from {{inh|bar|gmw-pro|*noh}}, from {{inh|bar|gem-pro|*nuh}}, from {{de"
  body "r|bar|ine-pro|*nū-kʷe-}}. Cognates include {{cog|de|noch}}, {{cog|yi|נאָך|tr=nokh}} and {{cog|nl|nog}}, {{cog|nl|noch}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|bar|/ˈno/}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{bar-adverb}}\n\n"
  body "# [[still]], [[yet]] {{gloss|up to and including a given time}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Mia san '''no''' ned då.|We're not there '''yet'''.}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Des geht si '''no''' aus.|There's '''still''' time for"
  body " that.}}\n# [[yet]], [[eventually]] {{gloss|at an unknown time in the future}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Mia wern scho '''no''' åkumma.|We'll arrive '''eventually'''.}}\n# [[additionally]], [[in addition]], [[bes"
  body "ides]], [[else]]; {{ng|more often expressed in English with}} [[another]], [[more]]\n#: {{uxi|bar|'''No''' ana!|'''Another''' one!}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Foid da '''no''' wås ei?|Can you think of anything ''"
  body "'else'''?}}\n# (only) [[just]]; [[barely]] {{gloss|by a small margin}}\n#: {{uxi|bar|Is se gråd '''no''' ausgånga.|We made it '''just''' in time.}}\n# {{lb|bar|with comparative}} [[even]]\n#: {{uxi|ba"
  body "r|Des is jå '''no''' depperter.|That's '''even''' more stupid.}}\n\n==Catalan==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|ca|roa-oca|no}}, from {{inh|ca|la|nōn}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ca-IPA|ó}}\n* {{audio|ca"
  body "|LL-Q7026 (cat)-Unjoanqualsevol-no.wav|a=Catalonia}}\n* {{rhymes|ca|o|s=1}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|ca|interjection}}\n\n# {{l|en|no}} {{q|negation; commonly used to respond negatively to a ques"
  body "tion}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{ca-adv}}\n\n# [[not]], main negation marker\n#: {{ant|ca|sí|hoc}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|ca|'''No''' tinc diners.|'' No, I do not have money.''}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|ca|'''No''' fac"
  body "is això.|'' No, don't do that.''}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ca|no-res}}\n* {{l|ca|si més no}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|ca|pas}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ca-noun|m}}\n\n# [[no]]\n\n===Further reading="
  body "==\n* {{R:ca:IEC2}}\n* {{R:ca:GDLC}}\n* {{R:ca:DNV}}\n* {{R:ca:DCVB}}\n\n==Cebuano==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|ceb|noh||slang}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|ceb|es|no}}.\n\n===Interjection===\"
  body "n{{head|ceb|interjection}}\n\n# {{n-g|indicating surprise at, or requesting confirmation of, some new information; to express skepticism}}\n# {{n-g|indicating that what was just said was obvious and u"
  body "nnecessary; contrived incredulity}}\n\n==Chavacano==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|cbk|es|no||no}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{cbk-IPA}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{cbk-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|cbk|pseudoverb}} [[do]] [[n"
  body "ot]]; [[don't]] {{gl|used as a negative imperative}}\n\n==Czech==\n\n===Etymology===\nShort for {{m|cs|ano||yes}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{cs-IPA}}\n* {{audio|cs|LL-Q9056 (ces)-Ghost4Man-no.wav}}\"
  body "n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|cs|interjection}}\n\n# [[well]], [[why]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|cs|'''No''' ne!|'''Well''', I never!}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|cs|adverbs}}\n\n# [[certainly]], [[indeed]], [[o"
  body "f course]]\n# [[yeah]], [[yep]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|cs|no a co}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:cs:PSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:SSJC}}\n* {{R:cs:IJP}}\n\n==Dimasa==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|dis|nouns}}\"
  body "n\n# [[home]]\n\n==Dumbea==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|duf|/noː/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|duf|nouns}}\n\n# [[mosquito]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:map:ABVD|lang=ⁿDuᵐbea|id=1487|cite={{cite-book|au"
  body "thor=Leenhardt, M.|year=1946|title=Langues et dialectes de l'Austro-Mèlanèsie}}.}}\n* {{R:map:ABVD|lang=Drubea|id=1369|cite={{cite-book|title=Dictionnaire de la langue de Païta|author=Shintani, T.L.A."
  body " & Païta, Y.|year=1990|publisher=Sociéte d'etudes historiques de Nouvelle-Calédonie|location={{w|Nouméa}}}}.}}\n\n{{topics|duf|Dipterans|Parasites}}\n\n==Esperanto==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{eo-pr|a="
  body "LL-Q143 (epo)-Lepticed7-no.wav;LL-Q143 (epo)-Robin van der Vliet-no.wav}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{eo-head}}\n\n# {{Latn-def|eo|name|N|n}}\n\n====See also====\n{{list:Latin script letter names/eo}}\n\n===Inte"
  body "rjection===\n{{head|eo|interjection}} {{tlb|eo|rare}}\n\n# {{rfv-sense|eo}} {{lb|eo|neologism|nonstandard}} [[#English|no]]\n#: {{ant|eo|jes}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nUsed as an alternative to the mor"
  body "e generic {{l|eo|ne}}.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|eo|ne|gloss=no}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:eo:PIV 2020}}\n* {{R:eo:ReVo}}\n\n==Ewe==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{ee-IPA|nǒ}} {{q|noun}}\n* {{ee-"
  body "IPA|nò}} {{q|verb}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|ee|noun|head=nǒ}}\n\n# [[breast]]\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|ee|verb|head=nò}}\n\n# to [[drink]]\n# to [[suck]]\n\n==Fala==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fax-pr}}\n\n="
  body "==Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|fax|roa-opt|non}}, from {{inh|fax|la|nōn||not}}; probably influenced by {{der|fax|es|no}}.\n\n====Adverb====\n{{head|fax|adverbs}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|fax|non|t=no, not"
  body "}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{inh+|fax|roa-opt|no}}, equivalent to {{af|fax|nocat=1|en|o|t1=in|pos2=masculine singular definite article}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{l|fax|nu}} {{q|Lagarteiru, Val"
  body "verdeñu}}\n\n====Contraction====\n{{head|fax|contractions|g=m-s|plural|nos|feminine|na|feminine plural|nas}}\n\n# {{lb|fax|Mañegu}} [[in]] [[the]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:fax:Diccionariu|209}}\n\n="
  body "=Finnish==\n\n===Etymology===\nSimilar interjections can be found in other Finnic languages (compare {{cog|et|no}}, {{m|et|noh}}, {{cog|izh|no}}, {{cog|krl|no}}, {{cog|liv|no}}, {{m|liv|noh}}, {{cog|l"
  body "ud|no}}, {{cog|vot|no}}) and possibly also in other Uralic languages (compare {{cog|kpv|но}}, {{cog|udm|но}}). Compare also to those found in neighboring Indo-European languages (such as {{cog|sv|nå}}"
  body ", {{cog|lv|nu}}, {{cog|ru|ну}}), which may all trace back as far as {{cog|ine-pro|*nu}}. SSA concludes that the interjection is probably part original and part foreign.<ref>{{R:fi:SSA}}</ref>\n\n===Pr"
  body "onunciation===\n{{fi-pronunciation}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|fi|intj}}\n\n# [[well]]! {{gl|to acknowledge a situation; encouragement to answer or react; expressing the overcoming of reluctance t"
  body "o say something; exclamation of indignance}}\n#: {{alti|fi|noh}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|fi|'''No''' sepä mukavaa!|'''Well''', that’s nice.}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|fi|'''No''' kai meidän sitten pitää käydä kats"
  body "omassa.|'''Well''' I guess we have to go look then.}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|fi|'''No''', mikset mennyt juhliin?|'''Well''', why didn't you go to the party?}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|fi|Siellä oli, '''no''', aik"
  body "a tylsää.|It was, '''well''', pretty boring there.}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|fi|'''No''', et sinä nyt noin voi käyttäytyä!|'''Well'''! You can't behave like that!}}\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n=="
  body "=Further reading===\n* {{R:fi:KTSK|accessdate=2023-07-03}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|fi|a=no|-on|on}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|fr|nº|Nº}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-"
  body "IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Lyokoï-no.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|fr|noun|g=m}}\n\n# {{abbreviation of|fr|numéro|t=[[number]]}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|fr|on}}\n\"
  body "n==Friulian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|fur|la|nōn}}.\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|fur|adverbs}}\n\n# [[no]]\n#: {{ant|fur|sì}}\n\n==Fula==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|ff}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|ff|adverb"
  body "s}}\n\n# [[how]]?\n\n==Galician==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{gl-pr|nŏ}}\n* {{hyph|gl|no}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom contraction of preposition {{m|gl|en||in}} + masculine article {{m|gl|o||the}}.\n\n="
  body "===Contraction====\n{{head|gl|contraction|g=m|feminine|na|masculine plural|nos|feminine plural|nas}}\n\n# [[in]] [[the]]\n#: {{ux|gl|Pois eu anque lexos estaba do conde ben o vin '''no''' tempro.|Well"
  body ", even though I was from the count's house, I saw him well '''in the''' temple.}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom a mutation of {{m|gl|o}}.\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|gl|pronoun|g=m|accusative|cat2=persona"
  body "l pronouns}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|gl|o|t=[[him]]}}\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nThe ''n-'' forms of accusative third-person pronouns are used when the preceding word ends in ''-u'' or a diphthong, "
  body "and are suffixed to the preceding word.\n\n===See also===\n{{gl-personal pronouns}}\n\n===Related terms===\n{{col3|gl|lo|na|o}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:gl:DRAG}}\n* {{R:gl:Estraviz}}\n* {{R:gl:DDGM"
  body "}}\n* {{R:gl:CX}}\n* {{R:gl:DDLG}}\n\n==Garo==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|grt|nouns}}\n\n# [[younger sister]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|grt|nogipa}} {{qualifier|formal}}\n* {{l|grt|nono}}\n\n==Guinea-Biss"
  body "au Creole==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|pov|pt|nós}}. Cognate with {{cog|kea|nu}}.\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|pov|pronouns}}\n\n# [[we]]\n\n==Hawaiian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|haw}}\n\n===Pronunciatio"
  body "n===\n* {{haw-IPA}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{head|haw|prepositions}}\n\n# [[for]], [[belonging]] to, [[from]]\n\n====Usage notes====\n* Used for possessions that are inherited, out of personal control,"
  body " and for things that can be got into (houses, clothes, cars), while {{m|haw|na}} is used for acquired possessions.\n\n==Hone==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|juh|nouns}}\n\n# [[husband]]\n\n===Further reading="
  body "==\n* Anne Storch, ''Hone'', in ''Coding Participant Marking: Construction Types in Twelve African Languages'', edited by Gerrit Jan Dimmendaal\n\n==Ido==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{io-bor|no|non||no||no}}"
  body " Paronym to {{m|io|ne}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{io-IPA}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|io|interjection}}\n\n# [[#English|no]]\n#: {{ant|io|yes}}\n\n==Ingrian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nCognate with "
  body "{{cog|fi|no}} and {{cog|et|no}}. It is uncertain whether this word is natively Finnic or a borrowing from an {{ncog|ine|-}} language (compare {{ncog|ru|ну}} and {{ncog|sv|nå}}).\n\n====Pronunciation=="
  body "==\n* {{izh-p}}\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|izh|interjection}}\n\n# [[well]]\n#* {{RQ:izh:Lukukirja-1:1936|'''No''' nii, peen - vastajaa Valja.|'''Well''' yes, small - Valja replies.|page=12}}\n\n"
  body "=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|izh|nu}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{bor+|izh|ru|но}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{izh-p}}\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|izh|conjunctions}}\n\n# [[but]]\n#* {{RQ:izh:Geografia"
  body "-1:1936|'''No''' määmmä tunniin, toisen, a laageria ei oo.|'''But''' we walk for an hour, another, and the camp isn't there.|page=5}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|izh|mut}}, {{l|izh|vaa}}\n\n=====See "
  body "also=====\n* {{l|izh|odnako||however}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:izh:Nirvi:1971|page=343}}\n\n==Interlingua==\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|ia|adverbs}}\n\n# [[#English|no]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|ia|'''No''', "
  body "ille non travalia hodie.|'''No''', he is not working today.}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ia-noun|s}}\n\n# [[#English|no]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|ia|Illa time audir un '''no'''.|She is afraid of hearing '''no'''.}}\n"
  body "\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|it|id=particle|:inh|la:nōn}}\n{{inh+|it|la|nōn}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|nò*<audio:It-no.ogg>}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|it|particle}}\n\n# {{l|"
  body "en|no}}\n#: {{ant|it|sì}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|it|dire di '''no'''|to say '''no'''}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{it-adv}}\n\n# [[not]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|it|Vieni o '''no'''?|Are you coming or '''not'''?}}\n#: {"
  body "{uxi|it|[[perché no|Perché '''no'''?]]|Why '''not'''?}}\n# {{n-g|Used at the end of a sentence as a sort of tag question or to emphasize a statement}}; [[isn't it so]], [[right]]\n#: {{syn|it|nevvero|"
  body "neh}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|it|Te l'ho già detto, '''no'''?|I already told you, '''right'''?}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n{{col|it\n|uno sì e uno no\n|sì e no\n|nossignore\n}}\n\n=====See also=====\n{{co"
  body "l|it\n|non\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{ety|it|id=Noh|:bor|ja:能<tr:nō><lit:[performing] [[skill]], [[talent]]>}}\n{{bor+|it|ja|能|tr=nō|lit=[performing] [[skill]], [[talent]]}}.\n\n====Alternative forms"
  body "====\n* {{alt|it|nō}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|nò**<audio:It-no.ogg>}}\n* Unlike the above word, this word may or may not trigger {{w|syntactic gemination}} in the following word.\n\n====Noun"
  body "====\n{{it-noun|m|#}}\n\n# [[Noh]] {{gloss|a type of Japanese drama}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n{{ety|it|id=anti-|:bor|en:no}}\n{{bor+|it|en|no}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{it-pr|nȯ°}}\n* Unlike the abo"
  body "ve words, this word is unstressed and never triggers {{w|syntactic gemination}} in the following word.\n\n====Determiner====\n{{it-det|inv=1}}\n\n# {{l|en|no}}, [[anti-]]; {{n-g|found in numerous expr"
  body "essions borrowed from English, such as {{m|it|no comment}}, and in [[pseudo-anglicism]]s such as {{m|it|no logo||anti-globalization}} and {{m|it|no-vax||anti-vax}} (also written {{m|it|no vax}})}}\n\n"
  body "==Jamaican Creole==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|jam|en|no}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|jam|/no/}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|jam|adv}}\n\n# [[no]]\n#: {{ux|jam|Im av '''no''' sta.|He has '''no''' si"
  body "ster.}}\n# [[not]]\n#: {{ux|jam|'''No''' fi waant a tong mek kau '''no''' taak.|'''Not''' for want of a tongue that a cow does '''not''' talk.}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{jam-verb}}\n\n# [[don't]], [[doesn't]]"
  body "\n#: {{ux|jam|Mi '''no''' nuo.|I '''don't''' know.}}\n#: {{ux|jam|Bot dat '''no''' pruuv se wa mi a du rait.|But that '''doesn't''' prove that what I am doing is right.}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {"
  body "{R:jam:majstro.com}}\n\n==Japanese==\n\n===Romanization===\n{{ja-romaji}}\n\n# {{Latn-def|ja|syllable|の|ノ|no}}\n\n==Kalasha==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|kls|sa|नव|tr=náva}}.\n\n===Numeral===\n{{head|k"
  body "ls|numerals}}\n\n# {{cln|kls|cardinal numbers}} [[nine]]; 9\n\n==Kapampangan==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{pam-IPA|no}}\n* {{hyph|pam|no}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{pam-head|pronoun|no}}\n\n# {{alt sp|pam|n"
  body "ala}}\n# {{alt sp|pam|nalu}}\n# {{alt sp|pam|nayu}}\n\n{{pam-personal pronouns}}\n\n===Particle===\n{{head|pam|particle}}\n\n# {{ng|indicates emphasis}}\n#: {{ux|pam|Kuwanan ku'''no'''.|I '''should no"
  body "w''' take '''them'''.}}\n#: {{ux|pam|Kanan ku'''no'''...|I'm gonna eat '''these now'''...}}\n# {{ng|indicates confirmation and clarification in a question, depending on intonation}}\n#: {{syn|pam|na|n"
  body "e}}\n#: {{ux|pam|Menanu '''no'''?|What is it '''now'''?}}\n#: {{ux|pam|Kayan mu'''no'''?|You '''sure''' you're gonna do it?}}\n\n==Kikuyu==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ki|/nɔ/}}\n\n===Particle===\"
  body "n{{head|ki|particles}}\n\n# (it is) [[only]]<ref>{{R:Benson1964|entry=no}}</ref>\n#: ''{{l|ki|gĩkũrũ kĩega no kĩratina|Gĩkũrũ kĩega '''no''' kĩratina}}.''<ref name=\""gjw2001\"">Wanjohi, G. J. (2001). '"
  body "'Under One Roof: Gĩkũyũ Proverbs Consolidated'', [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=exNlAAAAMAAJ&q=gikuru+kiega+no+kiratina&dq=gikuru+kiega+no+kiratina&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjGi8idvqPXAhUEbrwKHfNxBN"
  body "oQ6AEIJjAA p. 21]. Paulines Publications Africa.</ref> - The '''only''' good old thing '''is''' a [[sausage tree]] fruit (for fermenting [[muratina]]).\n#: ''{{l|ki|mũndũ ũtathiaga oigaga no nyina ũru"
  body "gaga wega|Mũndũ ũtathiaga oigaga '''no''' nyina ũrugaga wega}}.'' - One who does not travel says '''only''' his/her mother's cooking is good.\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|ki|conjunctions}}\n\n# [[but]"
  body "]<ref name=\""arb1960\"">Barlow, A. Ruffell (1960). ''Studies in Kikuyu Grammar and Idiom'', [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=5ahkAAAAMAAJ&q=no+only+but&dq=no+only+but&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj385CAmo"
  body "fXAhUKVbwKHZMDAfoQ6AEINDAC pp. 32, 235].</ref>\n#: ''{{l|ki|mĩano ndĩtukanagio no kanua|Mĩano ndĩtukanagio '''no''' kanua}}.'' - The [[diviner]]'s [[gourd]]s do not get confused, '''but''' a mouth doe"
  body "s.<ref name=\""gb1960\"">Barra, G. (1960). ''1,000 Kikuyu proverbs: with translations and English equivalents'', [https://books.google.co.jp/books?id=q95HAAAAMAAJ&q=miano+nditukanagio+no+kanua&dq=miano+"
  body "nditukanagio+no+kanua&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj7793hna7WAhWBVrwKHauLDpUQ6AEIKDAA p. 51]. London: Macmillan.</ref>\n\n===References===\n<references />\n\n==Ladin==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|lld|la|nōn}}"
  body ".\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|lld|adverbs}}\n\n# [[not]]\n# [[#English|no]]\n\n==Ladino==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|lad|non}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|lad|osp|no}}, {{m|osp|non||not}}, from {{"
  body "inh|lad|la|nōn}} (compare {{cog|ca|no}}, {{cog|gl|non}}, {{cog|fr|non}}, {{cog|it|no}}, {{cog|pt|não}}, {{cog|ro|nu}}, {{cog|scn|no}}, {{m|scn|nun}}, & {{cog|es|no}}).\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{audi"
  body "o|lad|lad-no.ogg|a=Paris}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{lad-adv|heb=נו}}\n\n# [[not]]\n#* {{quote-journal|lad\n|journal=Şalom\n|title=El Antisemitizmo De Oy\n|author=Dora Niyego\n|date=2018-2-7\n|url=https://ww"
  body "w.salom.com.tr/arsiv/haber/105826/el-antisemitzmo-de-oy\n|passage=Kritikar Israel '''no''' es el antisemitizmo.\n|t=Criticizing Israel is '''not''' antisemitism.}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{lad-intj|he"
  body "b=נו}}\n\n# [[no]] {{gl|[[nope]]}}\n#: {{ant|lad|si}}\n#* {{quote-book|lad|author=Miriam Raymond|editor=Matilda Koén-Sarano\n|title=De Saragosa a Yerushaláyim: kuentos sefaradís\n|url=https://books.go"
  body "ogle.com/books?id=vX_YAAAAMAAJ\n|location=Zaragoza\n|publisher=Ibercaja\n|year=1988|year_published=1995\n|page=67\n|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=vX_YAAAAMAAJ&q=kosta\n|ISBN=84-88793-49-9\"
  body "n|text='''''No''', sinyor bakal, esto kosta sólo siete!''\n|t='''No''', mister shopkeeper, this costs only seven!}}\n\n===Derived terms===\n{{col|lad|no es koza}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:lad:Folkma"
  body "sa}}\n\n==Latin==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|la|title=nō|:inh|itc-pro:*(s)nāō|text=++|tree=1}} Cognate with {{cog|grc|νάω}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{la-IPA|nō}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{la-verb|1.nopass|nō"
  body "|nāv}}\n\n# {{lb|la|intransitive}} to [[swim]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|la|'''Nat''' lupus inter oves.|The wolf '''swims''' between the sheep.}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|la|'''Nare''' contra aquam|To '''swim''' aga"
  body "inst the stream}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|la|Piger ad '''nandum'''|Slow at '''swimming'''}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|la|Ars '''nandi'''|The art of '''swimming'''}}\n#* '''1st century BC''', {{w|Lucretius}}, ''De r"
  body "erum natura'' iii. 479.\n#*: {{quote|la|Cum vini vis penetravit,<br>Consequitur gravitas membrorum, præpediuntur<br>Crura vacillanti, tardescit lingua, madet mens,<br>'''Nant''' oculi, clamor, sigulti"
  body "s, jurgia gliscunt. --\n|translation=When once the force of wine hath inly pierst,<br>Limbes-heavinesse is next, legs faine would goe,<br>But reeling cannot, tongue drawles, mindes disperst,<br>Eyes '"
  body "''swime''', ciries, hickups, brables grow.}}\n# {{lb|la|intransitive}} to [[float]]\n#: {{syn|la|fluitō}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|la|Carinae '''nant''' freto.|Ships '''float''' in the sea.}}\n# {{lb|la|poet"
  body "ic|intransitive}} to [[sail]], [[flow]], [[fly]], etc.\n#: {{ux|inline=1|la|Per medium classi barbara '''navit''' Athon.|The barbarian youth '''sailed''' its fleet through the middle of Athos.}}\n#: {"
  body "{ux|inline=1|la|Undae '''nantes''' refulgent.|The '''flowing''' waves glitter.}}\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{la-conj|1.nopass|nō|nāv}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|la\n|adnō\n|enō\n|innābilis\n|[[nan"
  body "s|nāns, nantis]]<t:[[swimming]], [[floating]]>\n|[[nans|nāns, nantis]]<t:a [[swimmer]]><g:m>\n|natō\n|trānō\n|nāre sine cortice<t:to do without a guardian><lit:to swim without corks>\n|nāre per aestat"
  body "em liquidam<t:to [[fly]]><lit:to swim through cloudless summer>\n}}\n\n===References===\n* [https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/resolveform?type=exact&lookup=no&lang=latin no] in {{cite-book|author=C"
  body "harlton T. Lewis and Charles Short|title=[[w:A Latin Dictionary|A Latin Dictionary]]|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|year=1879}}\n* [https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:tex"
  body "t:1999.04.0060:entry=no no] in {{cite-book|author=Charlton T. Lewis|title=An Elementary Latin Dictionary|publisher=Harper & Brothers|location=New York|year=1891}}\n<!--* {{R:M&A}}-->\n\n==Latvian==\n\"
  body "n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|lv|ine-bsl-pro|*nō|t=on, onto}}, from {{inh|lv|ine-pro|*h₂en-|t=on, onto}}.\n\n===Preposition===\n{{head|lv|prepositions}}\n\n# [[from]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|lv|skaitīt '''no"
  body "''' viens līdz desmit|to count '''from''' one to ten}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|lv|viņš ir '''no''' Latvijas|he is '''from''' Latvia}}\n# [[out of]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|lv|iziet '''no''' istabas|to go '''out o"
  body "f''' the room}}\n# [[for]]\n# [[of]]\n#: {{ux|inline=1|lv|viens '''no''' viņa draugiem|one '''of''' his friends}}\n#: {{ux|inline=1|lv|izgatavots '''no''' koka|made '''of''' wood}}\n# [[with]]\n#: {{u"
  body "x|inline=1|lv|'''no''' sirds|'''with''' all one's heart}}\n\n==Lingala==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|ln|bni|no}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|ln|verb}}\n\n# to [[fall]] (rain), to [[rain]]\n\n==Livonian==\n\"
  body "n===Etymology===\nCompare {{cog|fi|no}}, {{cog|et|no}}; see the former for more.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{liv-p}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|liv|interjection}}\n\n# [[well]]\n\n===References===\n*"
  body " {{R:liv:LEL|no}}\n\n==Lombard==\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|lmo|adverbs}}\n\n# {{alternative spelling of|lmo|nò}}\n\n==Louisiana Creole==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|lou|Probably from French \""nous\"" or a "
  body "clipping of Louisiana Creole \""nouzòt\"" and/or French \""nous autres\"".}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|lou|/no/}}\n* {{rhymes|lou|o|s=1}}\n* {{homophones|lou|nô}}\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|lou|pronou"
  body "n|cat2=personal pronouns}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|lou|nouzòt|t=we, us}}\n\n==Lower Tanana==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|taa|ath-pro|*noˑ}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|taa|not}}\n"
  body "\n====Postposition====\n{{head|taa|postposition}}\n\n# [[sign]] of, [[premonition]] of, [[omen]] of\n# [[recurring]] event of\n\n====Root====\n{{head|taa|root}}\n\n# to [[move]], [[tremble]], [[shake]"
  body "]; for there to be an [[earthquake]]\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|dur|no|no'|noɬ|no'}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|mom|noyh|nonh|noɬ|no'}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|cust|noyh|n"
  body "oyh|noyh|noyh}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|taa\n|sronot<t:early spring>\n|gheno<t:it is shaking>\n|ghini'i<t:maggots, rice>\n|noghenoyi<t:fresh fish>\n|ghedeno<t:he/sh"
  body "e labors, is industrious>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari24|page=331-332}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|taa|ath-pro|*naˑʷ}}. Cognate with {{cog|aht|naa}}, {{cog|nv|-NÁ}}.\n\n====Root====\n{{he"
  body "ad|taa|root}}\n\n# to [[nomadize]]\n# to [[live]] in or [[occupy]] an area\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|mom|nayh|no|naɬ|naɬ}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|cont|na'|no|na'|"
  body "na'}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|per|nayh|no|nayh|nayh}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|cust|niyh|niyh|niyh|niyh}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|neu|no'|no'|no'|no'}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|t"
  body "aa\n|ghenaɬna<t:band of people traveling>\n|Ninano'<t:Nenana River>\n|xwnoya<t:gyrfalcon>\n|Ninano' Xwt'ana<t:Nenana River band>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari24|page=332-334}}\n\n===Etymology 3="
  body "==\nFrom {{inh|taa|ath-pro|*naˑ}}. The cognate root appears in {{cog|aht|ʼelnaa||drudge, slave}}.\n\n====Root====\n{{head|taa|root}}\n\n# to [[capture]], [[work]] for\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem"
  body "-set-header}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row2|neu|{{l|taa|no}}|{{l|taa|no'}}|{{l|taa|noɬ}}|—}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row2|conc|—|{{l|taa|nonh}}|—|—}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|taa\n|e"
  body "lno<t:captive, slave>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari24|page=329}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nFrom {{inh|taa|ath-pro|*ŋaˑ}}, {{m|ath-pro|*ŋeˑ}}. Cognate with {{cog|aht|naa}}.\n\n====Root====\n{{head|ta"
  body "a|root}}\n\n# to become [[depleted]], [[exhausted]]; plural subjects [[die]]\n\n=====Stem set=====\n{{aht-stem-set-header}}\n{{taa-stem-set-row|conc|na|nonh|naɬ|naɬ}}\n{{aht-stem-set-footer}}\n\n====="
  body "Derived terms=====\n{{col2|taa\n|ndena<t:it is leaking>\n|nena<t:they die one by one>\n}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari24|page=330}}\n\n===Etymology 5===\nRelated to {{af|taa|no-|t1=across}}.\n\n==="
  body "=Postposition====\n{{head|taa|postposition}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|taa|noda||across}}\n\n====References====\n* {{Kari24|page=336}}\n\n==Luxembourgish==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|lb|id=near|:in"
  body "h|gmh:nāh<ety:inh<goh:nāh>>|tree=1|text=++}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|lb|/noː/}}\n** {{rhymes|lb|oː|s=1}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{head|lb|preposition|+ dative}}\n\n# [[after]] (in time)\n# [[af"
  body "ter]] (in a sequence)\n# after (the further side of, past)\n# [[according to]]\n# [[to]], [[towards]] (a direction)\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|lb|no an no}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{lb-adj|sup2=näch"
  body "sten}}\n\n# [[nearby]], [[near]], [[nigh]]\n# [[close]], [[closely]] [[related]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{lb-decl-adj}}\n\n==Middle Dutch==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|dum|conjunction|head=nō}}\n\n# "
  body "{{alternative form of|dum|noch}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:VMNW|ID34382|II}}\n* {{R:MNW|32704|II}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|enm|/nɔː/|}}\n* {{q|early}} {{IPA|enm|/nɑ"
  body "ː/}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|enm|ang|nā,nō|pos=adj}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|enm|na}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{enm-adj}}\n\n# [[#English|no]]\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en"
  body "|no}}\n* {{desc|yol|na|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED Online|entry=nō|pos=adj|id=MED29602}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{inh+|enm|ang|nā}}, {{m|ang|nō}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alte"
  body "r|enm|na}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{enm-adv}}\n\n# [[not]]\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|en|no}}\n* {{desc|en-geo|ne}}\n* {{desc|sco|nae}}\n* {{desc|yol|no|alts=1}}\n\n=====References=====\n* {{R:MED"
  body " Online|entry=nō|pos=adv|id=MED29603}}\n\n==Mizo==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|lus|cup}}\nFrom {{inh|lus|tbq-kuk-pro|*naw|t=cup}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|lus|noun}}\n\n# [[cup]], [[mug]]\n\n===Ety"
  body "mology 2===\n{{etymid|lus|young}}\nFrom {{inh|lus|tbq-kuk-pro|*naw|t=young}}.\n\n====Adjective====\n{{lus-adj}}\n\n# [[young]], [[tender]]\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|lus|nau}}\n\n===Further rea"
  body "ding===\n* {{R:lus:Lorrain}}\n\n==Mòcheno==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|mhn|ine-pro|*h₂neḱ-}}\n{{inh+|mhn|gmh|nāch}}, from {{inh|mhn|goh|nāh}}. Cognate with {{cog|cim|nå}} and {{cog|de|nach}}; see ther"
  body "e for more.\n\n===Preposition===\n{{head|mhn|prepositions}}\n\n# {{lb|mhn|+ dative}} [[after]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|mhn|nomitto}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:CLM}}\n\n==Mokilese==\n\n===Pron"
  body "unciation===\n* {{IPA|mkj|/ˈno/|[ˈnõ]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|mkj|noun}}\n\n# [[wave]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|mkj|nohno}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:mkj:MED|page=172}}\n\n==Nalögo==\n\n===Nou"
  body "n===\n{{head|nlz|noun}}\n\n# [[fish]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nlz:Alfarano:2021|page=98}}\n\n==Narua==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|nru|sit-pro|*na-ŋ||you}}.\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|nru|pronoun|cat2"
  body "=personal pronouns}}\n\n# [[you]] {{q|singular}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{rfc|njz|manual inflection table should be moved to a template}}\n{| class=\""inflection inflection-table\""\n! NOM\n| {{l|njz|no"
  body "}}\n|-\n! ACC\n| {{l|njz|nom}}\n|-\n! DAT\n| {{l|njz|nokégébé}}\n|-\n! ABL\n| {{l|njz|nokélo}}\n|-\n! GEN\n| {{l|njz|noké}}\n|-\n! COM\n| {{l|njz|nolékobé}}\n|}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Alternati"
  body "ve forms===\n* {{alt|no|nå|nu}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|nb|adverbs}}\n\n# {{lb|nb|obsolete}} [[now]] {{gloss|this very moment}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nPart of the \""Nazi reform\"" of 1941, made during"
  body " Norwegian occupation by Germany. Almost exclusively used in texts made under occupation, and not generally considered a part of the official Bokmål chronology.\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Alternat"
  body "ive forms===\n* {{alt|nn|nu|nå||dialectal}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|nn|non|núna}}, derived from {{m|non|nú}}.\n\n{{s|interjection}} May be related to Finno-Ugric, like {{m+|fi|-}} and {{cog|et|no}}"
  body ", {{cog|izh|no}}, {{m+|kpv|но}}, {{m+|udm|но}}. Compare also {{cog|sv|nå}}, {{m+|lv|nu}} and {{m+|ru|ну}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nn|/nuː/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nn-noun-n1}}\n\n# [[moment]]; poi"
  body "nt in [[time]]\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|nn|adverbs}}\n\n# [[now]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nn|noverande}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|nn|interjection}}\n\n# used when finding something out; wh"
  body "en being irritated\n#* {{quote-book|nn|year=1861|author=w:Aasmund Olavsson Vinje|title=Ferdaminni fraa Sumaren 1860|text=Der maa '''no''' vera nokot smaatt fint Gras imillom, som Femulen finner, for e"
  body "llers kunde der ikki bu annat Liv enn Reinsdyret.|t=There must be some small fine grass in between for the cattle to find, otherwise no other life than the reindeer could live there.}}\n#* {{quote-boo"
  body "k|nn|year=1851|author=w:Ludvig Mathias Lindeman|title=Liti Kjersti og bergekongen<qq:transcription of an oral song>|text=Gakk '''no''' deg i Stova inn|t=Go (you) inside the house}}\n#* Det kan '''no''"
  body "' faen ikkje stemme at traktor'n var så billeg\n#*: It can't be damn right that the tractor was so cheap\n#* Er det '''no''' sånn at dåkk vil ikkje bli med på fjellturen?\n#*: Is it so, that ya'll don"
  body "'t want to join on the mountain trip?\n#* Eg skulle '''no''' vore på elgjakta no, men i staden for det må eg vera her og rydde.\n#*: I was supposed to be on the moose hunt now, but I must be here and "
  body "clean up instead.\n#* Kom igjen '''no''' då!\n#*: C'mon!\n#: {{syn|nn|altso|då}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n==Notsi==\n\n===Particle===\n{{head|ncf|particles}}\n\n# {{n-g|plural marker}}\n\"
  body "n===Further reading===\n* ''Language Complexity: Typology, Contact, Change'', edited by Matti Miestamo, Kaius Sinnemäki, Fred Karlsson\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{affix|ang|ne|ā}}\n\n===P"
  body "ronunciation===\n* {{ang-IPA|nō}}\n* {{rhymes|ang|oː|s=1}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{ang-adv|nō}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|ang|nā}}\n\n==Old Galician-Portuguese==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|roa-op"
  body "t|eno|ẽno}}\n\n===Contraction===\n{{head|roa-opt|contraction}}\n\n# {{contraction of|roa-opt|en|o}}\n#* {{quote-book|roa-opt|year=1291|editor=E. Cal Pardo|title=Colección diplomática medieval do arqui"
  body "vo da catedral de Mondoñedo|location=Santiago|publisher=Consello da Cultura Galega|page=79\n|passage=''et disso que despenderan en tres ueces que fora a San Cibrao a pinnorar a balea et a entregala cc"
  body "c mor. et disso que ennas pinnaças et '''no''' trager da balea metera c mor. et quandor foronon o maestreescola et don Pedro Dias a San Cibrao con quinentos ommes et con xxx a caualo por tomar esta ba"
  body "lea aos ommes do infante''\n|t=And he said that he spent, in three times that he went to San Cibrao to pawn the whale and to deliver it, 300 mor.; and he said that in the pinnaces and '''in the''' del"
  body "ivery of the whale he spent 100 mor.; and when the schoolmaster and lord Pedro Dias went to San Cibrao with five hundred peons and 30 mounted men, for seizing the whale from the prince’s men.}}\n\n==="
  body "=Descendants====\n* {{desc|fax|no}}\n* {{desc|gl|no}}\n* {{desc|pt|no}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:roa-opt:DDGM}}\n\n==Old Irish==\n\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|sga|conjunctions}}\n\n# {{alt sp|sga|nó}"
  body "}\n\n==Old Occitan==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|pro|non}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|pro|la|non}}.\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|pro|adverbs}}\n\n# [[#English|no]]\n#: {{ant|pro|oc}}\n\n====Descend"
  body "ants====\n* {{desc|oc|non}}\n\n==Old Spanish==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|osp|non}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|osp|la|nōn||not}}.\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|osp|adverb}}\n\n# [[not]]\n#* {{Q|osp"
  body "|Diego de San Pedro|Cárcel de Amor|151|year=1492|quote=Lo cual yo '''no''' niego, pero atrevime a ello pensando que me harías merced '''no''' segund quien la pedía, mas segund tú, que la haviés de dar"
  body "|t=I deny this '''not''', but I dared to do it thinking that you would forgive me, '''not''' because of who was asking for forgiveness, but because it is proper of you, who had to do it}}\n\n====Desce"
  body "ndants====\n* {{desc|lad|no|נו}}\n* {{desc|es|no}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:osp:TDMS|358}}\n\n==Pali==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n{{pi-alt}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|pi|sa|नस्|नः|t=us}}.\n\n==="
  body "=Pronoun====\n{{head|pi|pronoun forms}}\n\n# {{inflection of|pi|ahaṃ||acc//ins//gen//dat|p|t=us}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{inh+|pi|sa|नो|t=and not}}.\n\n====Particle====\n{{pi-particle}}\n\n# surely no"
  body "t\n# indeed not\n\n=====Usage notes=====\nSometimes reinforced by {{m|pi|na||not}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|pi|no ce||unless}}\n* {{l|pi|noce||unless}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nEmphatic form of "
  body "{{m|pi|nu||then, now}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{pi-particle}}\n\n# indeed, then, now\n\n===References===\n{{R:pi:PTS}}\n\n==Papiamentu==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|pap|pt|não}} and {{der|pap|es|no}} and"
  body " {{der|pap|kea|nau}}.\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|pap|adverbs}}\n\n# {{l|en|no}}\n# [[not]]\n\n==Plautdietsch==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|pdt|gml|nâ}}, from {{inh|pdt|osx|nāh}}.\n\n===Preposition===\"
  body "n{{head|pdt|prep}}\n\n# [[towards]]\n#: {{syn|pdt|opptoo}}\n# [[near]]\n#: {{syn|pdt|dichtbie}}\n# {{q|as a prefix}} [[after]]\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|pdt|Noheit|t=vicinity}}\n\n==Polabian==\n"
  body "{{Wiktionary:Picture dictionary/pox:prep-place}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|pox|sla-pro|*na}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|pox|/no/}}\n\n===Preposition===\n{{pox-prep|}}\n\n# [[on]]\n\n==Polish==\"
  body "n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|a=Pl-no.ogg|hh=-no|prz=#|pdg=#|bie=#|krk=#|pod=#|sbl=#|mas=#|pdl=#}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|pl|:clipping|ano<ref:{{R:pl:Bańkowski|no II}}>|etydate=19th century<ref"
  body ":{{R:pl:SJP1900||398|3}}>|id=yeah|tree=+|text=+}} Compare {{cog|cs|no}}, {{cog|szl|no}}, {{cog|sk|no}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|pl|ną||Western Kraków|Bochnia|Wadowice|Biecz|Ropczyce|Żywi"
  body "ec|Podhale|Zakopane|Skawa}}\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|pl|interjection}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|colloquial|or|Podlachia|Drohiczyn|Western Kraków|Kraków|Bochnia|Wadowice|Myślenice|Pisarzowice|Biecz dialect|"
  body "Ropczyce|Podhale|Zakopane|Rabka-Zdrój}} [[yeah]], [[yep]]\n#: {{syn|pl|ano|tak}}\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|pl|nu||Far Masovian}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|pl|particle}}\n\n# {{ng|used "
  body "to state the speaker thinks something is obvious and that one should not ponder further}}; [[well]], well [[yeah]]\n# {{ng|used to state that the speaker thinks everything that can be said has been sa"
  body "id and would like to finish the topic}}\n# {{lb|pl|colloquial|hedge}} {{ng|expresses uncertainty}}; [[well]]\n# {{lb|pl|usually as a question}} {{ng|used to encourage the conversation partner to give "
  body "a response}}; [[well]]?\n# {{lb|pl|often extended}} {{ng|used to express surprise, awe, or caution}}\n# {{lb|pl|colloquial|or|Western Kraków|Zebrzydowice}} {{n-g|[[filled pause|Filled pause]], usually"
  body " connecting a previous sentence}}; [[well]]\n# {{ng|introduces a question, often lightly emotionally charged}}\n# {{ng|used to draw attention to the current situation}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{ety|pl|"
  body ":clipping|jeno<ref:{{R:pl:Bańkowski|no I}}>|etydate=1749<ref:{{R:pl:SXVII|NO|51617|AW|07.12.2021}}>|id=cmon|tree=+|text=+}} Compare {{cog|szl|no}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alt|pl|ną||Western"
  body " Kraków|Bochnia|Wadowice|Biecz|Ropczyce|Żywiec|Podhale|Zakopane|Skawa}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|pl|particle}}\n\n# {{lb|pl|originally dialectal|Western Kraków|Bochnia|Wadowice|Podegrodzie|Nowy Sąc"
  body "z|Biecz|Ropczyce|Podhale|Zakopane}} {{ng|emphatic particle used with imperatives to speed up a performed action}}; [[c'mon]], [[now]]\n#: {{syn|pl|ano}}\n#: {{ux|pl|'''No''', rusz się! Swiatło jest zi"
  body "elone!|'''C'mon''', move! The light is green!}}\n#* {{quote-book|pl|year=1841|author=Józef Ignacy Kraszewski|title=Szkice obyczajowe i historyczne|page=171|text={{nb...}} wróciwszy z kluczem na posłan"
  body "ie. — Niech mnie licho porwie, jeśli cię puszczę — musisz zostać z nami. — O! figle! '''no'''! '''no'''! daj '''no''' klucza, rzekł śmiejąc się Alexy, daj '''no''', serce, klucza! daj!|t={{nb...}} hav"
  body "ing returned with the key. \""Goddamn it, if I let you go, you'll have to stay with us.\"" \""Oh! Jokes! '''Cmon'''! '''Cmon'''! '''Cmon''', give the key!\"" Alex said laughing. \""'''Cmon''', heart, give "
  body "the key!\""}}\n## {{lb|pl|Southern Borderlands|Kamianets-Podilskyi}} {{ng|used to urge a horse}}; [[hyah]]!\n# {{lb|pl|Masurian|Western Kraków}} {{syn of|pl|jeno}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|pl|"
  body "title=particle|no ba}}\n\n===Trivia===\n{{pl-freq 1990|3|0|7|106|484|600|76|293|1}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pl:WSJP}}\n* {{R:pl:PWN}}\n* {{R:pl:SJP1807}}\n* {{"
  body "R:pl:SJP1861}}\n* {{R:pl:SGP1900||330|3}}\n* {{R:pl:NFJP}}\n* {{R:pl:Saloni:1908||342}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pt-IPA}}\n* {{audio|pt|LL-Q5146 (por)-JnpoJuwan-no.wav|a=<<Brazil>> "
  body "(<<São Paulo>>)}}\n* {{audio|pt|LL-Q5146 (por)-Santamarcanda-no.wav|a=<<Portugal>> (<<Porto>>)}}\n* {{hyph|pt|no}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|pt|roa-opt|no}}, clipping of {{m|roa-opt|eno}}, from {{m"
  body "|roa-opt|en||in}} + {{m|roa-opt|o||the}}.\n\n====Contraction====\n{{pt-contr-adj}}\n\n# {{senseid|pt|em o}} {{contraction of|pt|em|o|lit=[[in]] [[the]], [[on]] the}}\n#* {{quote-book|pt|year=2003|auth"
  body "or=w:J. K. Rowling; w:Lia Wyler|title=Harry Potter e a Ordem da Fênix|publisher=Rocco|page=546\n|passage=Está na hora de testarmos os nossos talentos '''no''' mundo real, você não acha?|t=It's time to"
  body " test our talents '''in the''' real world, don't you think?}}\n\n=====Quotations=====\n{{see citations|pt}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Pronoun====\n{{head|pt|pronoun forms}}\n\n# {{senseid|pt|pronoun"
  body "}} {{pt-pronoun-with-n|m|sg}}\n#: {{ux|pt|Eles removeram-'''no''' do grupo devido a mau comportamento da sua parte.|They removed '''him''' from the group due to bad behavior on his behalf.}}\n#: {{ux|"
  body "pt|Costumava estar aqui um copo, mas eles partiram-'''no''' quando cá estiveram.|There used to be a glass here, but they broke '''it''' when they were here.}}\n\n=====Quotations=====\n{{see citations|"
  body "pt}}\n\n==Rohingya==\n{{cardinalbox|rhg|8|9|10|añcto|doc}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|rhg|𐴕𐴡}} - {{w|Hanifi Rohingya script}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{der+|rhg|sa|नव|t=nine|tr=náva}}.\n\n===Numera"
  body "l===\n{{head|rhg|numeral|Hanifi spelling|𐴕𐴡}}\n\n# [[nine]]\n\n{{cln|rhg|cardinal numbers}}\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ro|/nɔ(ː)/|/no/}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|ro|interject"
  body "ion}}\n\n# {{lb|ro|Transylvania}} [[well]], [[so]]\n\n==Scottish Gaelic==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|gd|neo|na|nà}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|gd|sga|nó}}, {{m|sga|nú}}, from {{inh|gd|cel-p"
  body "ro|*nowe}} (compare {{cog|cy|neu}} and {{cog|obt|nou}}).\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|gd|/na/|/nɔ/|ref2={{R:gd:Oftedal}} !!! {{R:gd:Borgstrom1937}} !!! {{R:gd:Wentworth:2003}}}}\n* {{hyph|gd|no}}\n"
  body "\n===Conjunction===\n{{head|gd|conjunctions}}\n\n# [[or]]\n# [[nor]]\n# [[neither]]\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|gd|air neo}}, {{l|gd|air dheadh}}, {{l|gd|deadh}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|siz"
  body "e=smaller}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|sh|sla-pro|*nъ}}, ({{cog|ru|но}}, {{m|ru|ну}}), from {{der|sh|ine-bsl-pro|*nu}} ({{cog|lt|nu}}), from {{der|sh|ine-pro|*nu|t=now}}, ({{co"
  body "g|la|nunc|nun-c}}, {{cog|grc|νῦν}}).\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{sh-IPA|no}}\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{sh-con}}\n\n# {{lb|sh|after a comparative|regional|dated|expressive}} [[than]] (={{l|sh|nȅgo}},"
  body " {{l|sh|ȍd}})\n#: {{coi|sh|bolji '''no''' on|better '''than''' him}}\n#: → (= modern) {{coi|sh|bolji nego on/bolji od njega|better than him}}\n#: {{uxi|sh|Izgledaš bolje '''no''' ikad.|You're looking "
  body "better '''than''' ever.}}\n#: {{uxi|sh|Proračunski manjak Grčke u bio je značajno veći '''no''' što je vlada proc(ij)enila.|Greece's budget deficit was significantly bigger '''than''' the government h"
  body "ad estimated.}}\n# {{lb|sh|denoting exclusion}} [[but]], [[however]]\n#: {{uxi|sh|Pogrešno, '''no''' bio si dosta blizu.|Wrong, '''but''' you were pretty close.}}\n#: {{uxi|sh|'''No''' os(j)ećam samo "
  body "sreću.|'''But''' I can't feel anything but happy.}}\n#: {{uxi|sh|Tekst nije savršen, '''no''' nije li mogao biti bolji?|The text is not perfect, '''but''' could it have been better?}}\n\n===Etymology "
  body "2===\n{{der+|sh|ja|能|tr=nō}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{sh-IPA|nȏ}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{sh-noun|nȏ|m}}\n\n# {{lb|sh|theater}} [[noh]] {{attn|sh|please check [12:01, 16 December 2017 (UTC)]}}\n\n==="
  body "Etymology 3===\nFrom the conjunction {{m|sh|no}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{sh-IPA|no}}\n\n====Particle====\n{{sh-pcl}}\n\n# {{lb|sh|in a dialog, when responding to the interlocutor}} [[damn right"
  body "]]!, [[you bet]]! very much so!\n\n===References===\n* {{R:sh:HJP|eF1uURU%3D}}\n* {{R:sh:HJP|eF1uURM%3D}}\n* {{R:sh:HJP|eF1uURY%3D}}\n\n==Shabo==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|sbf|verbs}}\n\n# [[go]]\n\n==Sia"
  body "ne==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|snp|nouns}}\n\n# [[water]]\n\n===References===\n* ''The Papuan Languages of New Guinea'' (1986, {{ISBN|0521286212}}\n\n==Silesian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{szl-pr|a=LL-Q30"
  body "319 (szl)-Vxern-#.wav}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{ety|szl|id=well|:clipping|ano|text=+|tree=1}} Compare {{cog|pl|no}}.\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|szl|particle}}\n\n# {{n-g|used to state the speaker thi"
  body "nks something is obvious and that one should not ponder further}}; [[well]], well [[yeah]]\n# {{lb|szl|usually as a question}} {{n-g|used to encourage the conversation partner to give a response}}; [["
  body "well]]?\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{ety|szl|id=c'mon|:clipping|ino|text=+|tree=1}} Compare {{cog|pl|no}}.\n\n====Particle====\n{{head|szl|particle}}\n\n# {{n-g|emphatic particle used with imperatives to s"
  body "peed up a performed action}}; [[c'mon]], [[now]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:szl:silling}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|es|osp|no}}, {{m|osp|non}}, from {{inh|es|la|nōn}} (compare {"
  body "{cog|ca|no}}, {{cog|gl|non}}, {{cog|fr|non}}, {{cog|it|no}}, {{cog|pt|não}}, {{cog|ro|nu}}, {{cog|scn|no}}/{{m|scn|nun}}).\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{es-pr}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{es-adv}}\n\n# [[not]"
  body "]\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|es|non||archaic}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|es|de no<ll:Ecuador>\n|anda que no\n|cómo no\n|cuando no\n|no más\n|no ni na\n|no obstante\n|quieras que n"
  body "o\n|si no\n|sí y no\n|y que no\n|ya no\n}}\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|es|interjection|head=¿no?}}\n\n# {{l|en|no}}\n#: {{ant|es|sí}}\n# [[eh]]?, [[right]]?, [[isn't it]]? {{gloss|used as a tag qu"
  body "estion, to emphasise what precedes, or to request that the listener express an opinion}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|es|nonada}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{es-noun|m|noes}}\n\n# {{l|en|no}}\n\n===Etymol"
  body "ogy 2===\nContracted form of {{der|es|la|numero}}, ablative singular of {{m|la|numerus||number}}.\n\n====Pronunciation====\n{{es-pr|número}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{es-noun|m}}\n\n# {{abbreviation of|es|nú"
  body "mero}}; [[no.]]\n\n=====Alternative forms=====\n* {{alt|es|№|No.|no.}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:es:DRAE}}\n* {{R:es:DA}}\n\n==Sranan Tongo==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{der|srn|en|no}}. For the "
  body "sense \""(more) than\"", possibly compare dialectical {{noncog|en|nor||than}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{srn-IPA}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|srn|adverbs}}\n\n# [[#English|no]]\n# [[not]]\n\n===Particle="
  body "==\n{{head|srn|particle}}\n\n# {{n-g|Used to construct comparative phrases involving a non-human standard}}<ref>\n{{cite-thesis|page=76-77\n|author=Jacques Arends\n|title=Syntactic Developments in Sra"
  body "nan\n|year=1989\n|url=https://www.dbnl.org/tekst/aren012synt01_01/aren012synt01_01_0005.php}}</ref>\n#: {{ux|srn|A nyan switi '''no''' todo.|lit=The food is tasti'''er than''' a toad|The food is delic"
  body "ious.}}\n#: {{ux|srn|A waran '''no''' hèl.|lit=It's hot'''ter than''' hell|It's awfully hot.}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Tagalog==\n\n===Particle===\n{{tl-head|particle|b=+}}\n\n# {{alt "
  body "sp|tl|'no}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|tl|a=no|on}}\n\n==Tok Pisin==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|tpi|en|no}}.\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|tpi|adverbs}}\n\n# [[not]]\n#* {{RQ:Buk Baibel|Jenesis|2|5|pas"
  body "sage=...i no gat diwai na gras samting i kamap long graun yet, long wanem, em i '''no''' salim ren i kam daun yet. Na i no gat man bilong wokim gaden.|5=...and no tree or kind of herb had appeared on "
  body "the earth yet, because he had '''not''' sent rain to come down yet. And there was no one to work the garden.}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|tpi|nogat}}\n\n==Vietnamese==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|"
  body "vi|mkh-vie-pro|*ɗɔː|t=[[satiated]]}}. Cognate with {{cog|mtq|-}} Bi {{m|mtq|đo}} and {{cog|aem||dɑː}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{vi-IPA}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{vi-adj|[[奴]], [[𩛂]]}}\n\n# [[full]] {{gl"
  body "oss|of the stomach}}\n#: {{syn|vi|no bụng}}\n#: {{ant|vi|đói}}\n#: {{ux|vi|Đang '''no'''.|I'm '''full'''.}}\n#: {{ux|vi|'''No''' bụng rồi.|My stomach's '''full'''.}}\n# {{lb|vi|archaic}} [[full]]; [[c"
  body "omplete]]\n# {{lb|vi|chemistry|of a [[solution]]}} [[saturated]]\n# {{lb|vi|chemistry|of an [[organic compound]]}} [[saturated]]\n\n====Usage notes====\n* In modern usages, ''no'' only refers to the s"
  body "tomach being full, or by extension, a person having had enough to eat.\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col3|vi|no nê|no ấm|ấm no|no đủ|no say|no đòn|no bụng đói con mắt|ăn no ngủ kĩ}}\n\n==Votic==\n\n===P"
  body "ronunciation===\n{{vot-p|J=+}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymid|vot|well}}\n{{rfe|vot}} Cognate with {{cog|fi|no}} and {{cog|izh|no}}.\n\n====Interjection====\n{{head|vot|interjections}}\n\n# [[well]]\n"
  body "\n===Etymology 2===\n{{etymid|vot|but}}\nBorrowed from {{bor|vot|ru|но}}.\n\n====Conjunction====\n{{head|vot|conjunctions}}\n\n# [[but]] {{gloss|when serving to contrast}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:v"
  body "ot:VKS|no}}\n\n==Walloon==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|wa|:inh|fro:nom}}\n{{inh+|wa|fro|nom}}, from {{inh|wa|la|nōmen|t=name}}, from {{inh|wa|ine-pro|*h₁nómn̥}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|wa|/n"
  body "ɔ/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{wa-noun|m}}\n\n# [[name]]\n\n==West Frisian==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|fy|ofs|nū}}, from {{inh|fy|gmw-pro|*nū}}, from {{inh|fy|gem-pro|*nu}}, from {{inh|fy|ine-pro|*nū|t=no"
  body "w}}.\n\n===Adverb===\n{{head|fy|adverbs}}\n\n# [[now]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fy|notiid}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:WFT|67431}}\n\n===Interjection===\n{{head|fy|interjection}}\n\n# [["
  body "eh]], [[isn't it]], [[true]] (at end of declarative sentence, forms question to prompt listener's agreement)\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:WFT|67431}}\n\n==White Hmong==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{"
  body "mww-pron}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|mww|hmx-pro|*ʔnu̯ɔmH|t=cold}}.<ref name=Ratliff>{{R:hmx-pro:Ratliff 2010|page=277}}</ref>\n\n====Adjective====\n{{head|mww|adj}}\n\n# {{lb|mww|of [[weather]]}} "
  body "[[cold]]\n#: {{uxi|mww|No no li.|It's cold.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|mww\n|tsho tiv no<t:sweater, warm jacket>\n}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{inh+|mww|hmx-pro|*ʔneinX|t=this}}.<ref name=Ratli"
  body "ff />\n\n====Determiner====\n{{head|mww|determiner}}\n\n# ''an [[indicator]] of [[current]] or [[present]] [[location]]: [[this]] ([[place]], [[time]], [[person]], [[thing]])''\n#: {{uxi|mww|lub tsev "
  body "no|this house}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|mww\n|hnub no<t:today>\n}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:mww:Heimbach|page=141}}\n<references />\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|yol|enm|no|no,"
  body " na}}, from {{inh|yol|ang|nā}}.\n\n====Alternative forms====\n* {{alter|yol|na}}\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{IPA|yol|/nɔː/|/naː/}}\n\n====Adverb====\n{{head|yol|adverbs}}\n\n# [[not]]\n#* {{quote-bo"
  body "ok|yol|year=1867|title=GLOSSARY OF THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY <ref name=\""Poole 1867\"">{{R:Poole 1867|page=32}}</ref>|passage=Aamezil cou '''no''' stoane.|translation=Themselves could '''not''' st"
  body "and.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|page=90|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=14|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Outh o'mee hoane ch'ull '''no''' part wi' Wathere.|translation=O"
  body "ut of my hand I'll '''not''' part with Walter.}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=SONG|number=2|page=108|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=Hea had '''no''' much wut,|tr"
  body "anslation=He had '''not''' much wit,}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|yol|canna}}\n* {{l|yol|dinna}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Determiner====\n{{head|yol|determiners}}\n\n# {{alt form|yol|na}}\n#"
  body "* {{quote-book|yol|year=1927|chapter=ZONG O DHREE YOLA MYTHENS|line=3 <ref name=\""Browne 1927\"">{{R:Browne 1927|page=129}}</ref>|title=THE ANCIENT DIALECT OF THE BARONIES OF FORTH AND BARGY, COUNTY WE"
  body "XFORD|passage=Vo '''no''' own caars.|translation=Whom '''no''' one cares.}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n==Zazaki==\n\n===Pronoun===\n{{head|zza|pronouns|masculine demonstrative}}\n\n# [[this"
  body "]]""}}"

response_0029_api_php_action_parse_pag
  url "https://en.wiktionary.org/w/api.php?action=parse&page=potato&prop=wikitext&formatversion=2&format=json&redirects=1"
  body "{""parse"":{""title"":""potato"",""pageid"":37487,""redirects"":[],""wikitext"":""==English==\n[[Image:Potato and cross section.jpg|thumb|right|250 px|An intact '''potato''' (vegetable, on the right) and a cross-s"
  body "ection of a second potato]]\n{{wp}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|potatoe||archaic|now|nonstandard}}\n* {{alter|en|p'tater|tater||dialectal or informal}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|en|es|pa"
  body "tata}}, itself borrowed from {{der|en|tnq|batata||[[sweet potato]]}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|pə-tāʹtō}}, {{rhymes|en|eɪtəʊ|s=3}}\n* {{IPA|en|/pəˈteɪ.təʊ/|a=England}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-pot"
  body "ato.ogg|a=RP|IPA=[pə̥ˈtʰɛɪ̯θ͇ɜɵ]}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Nattes à chat-potato.wav|a=RP|IPA=[pə̥ˈtʰɛi̯tʰɜʊ̈]}}\n* {{IPA|en|/pəˈteɪ.toʊ/|[-ˈteɪ.ɾoʊ]|a=North America}}, {{q|colloquial, sometimes}"
  body "} {{IPAchar|/pəˈteɪ.tə/}}<ref>{{R:Collins}}</ref><ref>{{R:MWO}}</ref>\n** {{audio|en|en-us-potato.ogg|a=US|IPA=[pə̥ˈtʰeˑɾo]}}\n* {{IPA|en|/pɵˈʈaʈo/|/pɵˈʈeʈo/|a=Indic}}, {{rhymes|en|ætəʊ|eɪtəʊ|s=3}}\n*"
  body " {{IPA|en|/poˈteɪ.to/|a=Philippines}}\n* {{IPA|en|/pəˈteto/|a=Scotland}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun|~|es}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|Q16587531}} A plant of species {{taxfmt|Solanum tuberosum|species}} or its ed"
  body "ible [[starchy]] [[tuber]].\n#: {{syn|en|potater|tato|tater}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Condensed Replies to Various Letters|editor=Leroy M[ilton] Yale| journal=Babyhood: The Mother’s Nursery Guide"
  body ", Devoted to the Care of Children| volume=VII| location=New York, N.Y.; London| publisher=Babyhood Publishing Company| year=1891| page=230| column=2| passage=Do not let your child have '''potato''' fo"
  body "r another year; he will probably take milk well enough after he is weaned.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=C[harles] F[ord] Langworthy; Caroline L[ouisa] Hunt|title=Cheese and Its Economical Uses in the "
  body "Diet|series=[[w:Farmers' Bulletin|Farmers’ Bulletin]] 487|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Government Publishing Office|Government Printing Office]]| year=1912| page=24| pageurl=h"
  body "ttps://archive.org/details/CAT87202469/page/24/mode/1up|passage=The protein value of this dish is equal to that of 1⅛ pounds of '''potato''' and beef, the fuel value, however, being much in excess of "
  body "these.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|journal=Annual Report of the Local Government Board for Scotland| year=1915| page=17| passage=A number of the children said that they had '''potato''' for breakfast, ''"
  body "'potato''' and herring for dinner, '''potato''' and milk for supper.}}\n#* '''1917''', {{w|Knut Hamsun}}, ''{{w|Growth of the Soil}}'', Book 1, [[s:Growth_of_the_Soil/Book_1/Chapter_4|Ch.4]], at p.34:"
  body "\n#*: What was that about '''potatoes'''? Were they just a thing from foreign parts, like coffee; a luxury, an extra? Oh, the potato is a lordly fruit; drought or downpour, it grows and grows all the "
  body "same. It laughs at the weather, and will stand anything; only deal kindly with it, and it yields fifteen-fold again. [...] A man may lack grain to make bread, but give him potatoes and he will not sta"
  body "rve. Roast them in embers, and there is supper; boil them in water, and there's a breakfast ready.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1961|author={{w|Harry E. Wedeck}}|title=Dictionary of Aphrodisiacs|publisher"
  body "=The Citadel Press|location=New York|page=195|passage=Although the '''potato''' actually has no exciting value, it was believed, in the seventeenth century, to possess definite aphrodisiac qualities, "
  body "and is frequent mentioned in this respect in Elizabethan drama.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|title=Climate Change and the Health of Nations|author=Anthony J. McMichael; Alistair Woodward; Cameron Muir|year=2"
  body "017|ISBN=9780190262952|page=213| passage='''Potatoes''' were introduced to Ireland in 1590 after being brought to Europe by Spanish conquistadores from their place of origin in the South American Ande"
  body "s.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2021 December 1|author=Nigel Harris|title=St Pancras and King's Cross: 1947| journal=RAIL| issue=945| page=42| text=The rocketing popularity of '''potatoes''' in Londo"
  body "n's diet led to the conversion of the temporary GNR passenger station north of the canal [...] as a dedicated '''potato''' terminal, whose significant traffic was stolen from coastal shipping.}}\n# {{"
  body "lb|en|obsolete}} A [[sweet potato]] ({{taxfmt|Ipomoea batatas|species}}).\n# {{lb|en|informal|UK}} A [[conspicuous]] [[hole]] in a [[sock]] or [[stocking]].\n#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1943|author={{w|"
  body "Agatha Christie}}|title=The Moving Finger|chapter=|url=|page=|text=She was untidily dressed as usual and there were '''potatoes''' in both heels.}}\n# A [[person]] or [[animal]] shaped like a potato, "
  body "that is, with a large [[belly]] and/or short legs.\n# {{n-g|Metaphor for a person or thing of little value.}}\n#* {{RQ:Smollett Reprisal|scene=ii|page=8|passage=I don't value Monſieur de Champignon a "
  body "rotten '''potatoe'''; {{...}}}}\n## {{lb|en|slang|offensive}} A [[mentally]] [[handicapped]] [[person]].\n## {{lb|en|humorous}} A [[camera]] that takes [[poor]]-[[quality]] [[picture]]s or [[video]]s."
  body "\n## {{lb|en|humorous|slang|computing}} An [[underpowered]] [[computer]] or other [[device]], especially when [[small]] in [[size]].<!--may relate to the \""potato-powered Web server\"" hoax-->\n##* {{q"
  body "uote-journal|en|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/overwatch-community-donates-pc-parts-to-fan-who-could-barely-run-it-at-800x600/| date=2017-03-17| author=Steven Messner| title=Overwatch community donates P"
  body "C parts to fan who could barely run it at 800x600| journal=PC Gamer| passage=When most people refer to their computers as a '''potato''' they're being hyperbolic, but not Ethan. He plays Overwatch at "
  body "800x600 resolution with all settings on low and is excited when he gets 30 fps.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-09-22-meet-the-people-making-music-with-mega-drive"
  body "s-and-guitars-from-game-boys| date=2019-09-22| author=Benjamin Burns| title=Meet the people making music with Mega Drives, Game Boys and gAtaris| journal=Eurogamer| passage=If you want to have a go ri"
  body "ght now, then Famitracker will let you compose songs for the NES and it'll run on a Windows-operated '''potato'''.}}\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|plant}} {{l|en|p'tater}} {{q|dialectal}}, {{l|en|spu"
